<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAY 92 / International Capital Markets: Bundesbank chief warns of E
Europe funding shortage
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON LONDON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MUNICH
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE developing countries of eastern Europe face a growing shortage of
funding unless action is taken to redress a global imbalance between the
supply of and demand for capital, Mr Hans Tietmeyer, deputy president of the
Bundesbank, warned yesterday.
Speaking at the annual conference of the International Securities Market
Association in Munich, Mr Tietmeyer forecast that long-term interest rates
in the world economy (and hence bond yields) would remain high because of an
imbalance between the supply and demand for capital.
While the developed industrial nations would face no major problems in
satisfying their capital needs, the developing countries - in particular
those of central and eastern Europe - would be hampered in efforts to
finance economic restructuring, he said.
Mr Tietmeyer argued the major exporters of capital - Germany, Japan, and the
OPEC oil-producing nations - would be less able to finance the world economy
in coming years because of problems close to home. Germany needs to make
substantial fiscal transfers to the eastern part of the country, Japan faces
a massive decline in asset prices and the OPEC countries faced low oil
revenues and the need to rebuild after the Gulf war.
However, demand for capital remained very high, he said. Mr Tietmeyer said
the low savings ratio in the US, combined with the growth of federal budget
deficit, meant 'that country will continue to suck in a major proportion of
world savings'.
In a wide-ranging defence of the Bundesbank's policy of high interest rates,
Mr Tietmeyer said high short-term rates were a major element in promoting
additional saving and reducing excess demand for capital in the private
sector.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
