   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES in McDonnell Douglas, the financially stretched US aerospace group,
plunged Dollars 5 5/8 to close at Dollars 47 1/8 yesterday - a fall of more
than 10 per cent - as Wall Street worries mounted over the fate of its
problem-plagued C-17 military aircraft.
The C-17 development programme is running more than a year behind schedule
and substantially over budget on the company's Dollars 6.6bn fixed price
contract.
The share price drop came in response to news of fresh production problems
on the aircraft and a call this week by the House of Representatives' Armed
Services committee for a 30 per cent cut in next year's funding for the
programme and a block on the C-17 going into full production.
Congressional ire was also increased by allegations from the Pentagon's
inspector general that the Air Force had connived in 1990 to provide secret
financial assistance to McDonnell Douglas by improperly rushing through
acceptance of the first completed C-17 when it was only 80 per cent
finished.
McDonnell Douglas has repeatedly denied asking for or receiving any bail-out
money.
