<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAY 92 / International Company News: Foster's to look at structure of
CUB
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FOSTER'S Brewing Group, the Australian beer, pastoral and finance group,
yesterday announced a review of the structure of its Carlton and United
Breweries (CUB) subsidiary, Australia's biggest brewer.
The review was announced by Mr Ted Kunkel, chief executive, as part of a
drive to recover market share lost to National Brewing, the former brewing
arm of Bond Corporation Holdings, now owned by Lion Nathan of New Zealand.
Mr Kunkel said the review was 'a normal part of a management's task in any
efficient organisation, and will ensure that the company is properly
focussed to meet the opportunities of the 1990s'.
However, the review is also in line with views expressed by Mr John Elliott,
deputy chairman of Foster's. Mr Elliott believes the group has failed to
extract full value from CUB's near-monopoly in Victoria, Australia's second
most populous state.
International Brewing Holdings (IBH), a private company controlled by Mr
Elliott, owns 38 per cent of Foster's, but will be in breach of loan
covenants on debts of about ADollars 2.5bn unless its bankers approve a
financial restructuring plan due to be delivered today.
The restructuring plan is believed to focus on a proposed merger of Foster's
with SA Brewing, the South Australian drinks and industrial group run by Mr
Ross Wilson.
The plan suggests the merger could be accomplished through a share swap
allowing IBH to repay much of its debt, and secure a return of about
ADollars 2.60 for Foster's shareholders, compared with last night's closing
price of ADollars 1.86.
The deal has not been approved by the boards of SA Brewing or Foster's, and
is understood to be opposed by Foster's directors, including Mr Nobby Clark,
chairman. The deal would also face significant regulatory problems,
including the need to gain approval from the Trade Practices Commission for
a further reduction in competition in Australia's highly concentrated
brewing market.
Analysts said the review of CUB was likely to help IBH persuade the banks to
roll over its debts, especially if it helps convince them that restructuring
the Australian brewing operations will lift Foster's earnings and dividends.
IBH depends on dividends from Foster's to pay interest on its debts, which
was acquired to fund the purchase of the Foster's shareholding - the
company's only asset. The shares are worth about ADollars 1.6bn.
The company's bank lenders include Hongkong Bank Australia and Citibank.
Analysts say the banks are unlikely to try to wind up the company in the
short term. The most likely outcome is a deal which would remove some of
IBH's debt and reduce the uncertainty surrounding the group.
</TEXT>
