FT  15 MAY 92 / UK Company News: King &amp; Shaxson dividend cut hits shares
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
KING &amp; Shaxson Holdings, the discount house, has proposed cutting its
dividend for the first time in its history following a halving in profit
from Pounds 1.8m to Pounds 920,000 after providing for rebate, tax and
transfer from contingencies in the year to April 30.
The final would be 2.5p for a total of 5p, against 10.25p. The shares lost
17p to close at 91p.
Mr David Pearce, who became chairman following the death of Mr Billy
D'Abbans in February, said it had been a troublesome period for the core
discount house business. He added that during the year the pivotal role of
the discount market as a provider of liquidity to the banking system had
been eroded.
'We are normally in an uncomfortable vice between eligible bill yields that
are forced too low and money costs that are pushed too high. It is for this
reason that our holdings of money market instruments are approximately half
that of a year ago.'
The situation was unsatisfactory, he said, and the company was looking at
further ways of reducing its dependence on the discount house.
The results include those of Smith St Aubyn (Holdings), the discount house.
