FT  15 MAY 92 / Shell shares rise on strong first-quarter results
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES in the Royal Dutch/Shell group, the Anglo-Dutch oil company gained
Pounds 1 3/32 to close at Pounds 46 5/8 yesterday as the company announced
surprisingly strong first-quarter results.
Increased earnings from exploration and production helped the company to
increase net income on a historical cost basis to Pounds 858m, up just over
1 per cent from Pounds 847m in the same period last year.
With the price of Brent crude around Dollars 3 a barrel lower than in the
first quarter of 1991, analysts had forecast figures of between Pounds 450m
and Pounds 650m. Current cost net income, which includes stock gains or
losses, fell 22 per cent to Pounds 954m from Pounds 1.23bn.
The figures reflected a strong performance in upstream and downstream
businesses outside North America. Shell said margins in its Asian market
remained relatively firm because of lower levels of export from the Middle
East and growth in demand.
Mr Fergus MacLeod, oil analyst at County NatWest in Edinburgh, said: 'These
are very intriguing figures and completely at variance with anything any
other company has managed to deliver. They reflect a great deal of success
in holding on to margins at the pumps and the refineries.'
Shell's oil production in the first quarter rose 6 per cent to 2.22m barrels
a day. Gas sales volumes also rose 9 per cent to 8.31bn cu ft a day.
Earnings in the exploration and production sector rose to Pounds 468m from
Pounds 443m last year, with higher production and special items including a
US contract settlement and tax adjustment more than offsetting the lower oil
price.
Downstream manufacturing and marketing earnings increased to Pounds 298m
from Pounds 254m, although they fell on a current cost basis to Pounds 390m
from Pounds 624m because of lower margins.
Gains from corporate items - including Pounds 85m from exchange rate
movements - also boosted the figures.
However, the chemicals sector saw income plummet to Pounds 21m from Pounds
89m in the same period in 1991. The 1991 figure was itself a drop of Pounds
70m from 1990. Most of the reduction was in the market outside the US, where
lower product margins reflected depressed markets, particularly for bulk
petrochemicals.
