<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAY 92 / Parliament and Politics: Beckett launches campaign
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A CALL for state funding of political parties and limits on parties'
national spending on the general election headed the agenda as Mrs Margaret
Beckett, shadow chief secretary, launched her election address for the
Labour party deputy leadership yesterday.
Campaigning, like others, on a platform of modernising the party, Mrs
Beckett promised that her first priority as deputy leader would be to set up
policy forums as a way of giving individual party members a greater say in
formulating policy.
Mr Bryan Gould, the shadow environment secretary, as part of his leadership
campaign, put forward a vigorous defence of the role of the public sector
delivering services. He also criticised the government's approach to
compulsory competitive tendering.
In a speech to the Fire Brigade Union's annual conference, Mr Gould said
that Labour should 'loudly proclaim that there are some services that can
only be done properly within the public sector,' while maintaining pressure
on the services to improve.
Nominations for the Labour party's shadow cabinet elections and a contest
for the posts of chief whip and parliamentary party chairman are to go ahead
before the leadership is settled.
With an early summer recess expected soon after the leadership contest
finishes on July 18, senior officers of the PLP have decided to bring both
processes forward to avoid delays.
</TEXT>
