<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAY 92 / Councils face delay over budget targets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE COUNCIL tax looks likely to run into trouble in its first year because
the announcement of next year's overall local-government spending will
probably be delayed.
Meanwhile, ministers faced criticism when Mr Michael Howard, the environment
secretary, announced that the government intended to 'cap' 10 councils'
spending this year.
Each July the government usually announces the maximum amount it believes
local government should spend in the following financial year (total
standard spending) and the total amount of external support through
government grant and the business rate. This year, though, The Department of
the Environment believes the statement may be delayed until October.
The likelihood of a hold-up is being interpreted as a sign of how tight the
coming public spending round will be.
Environment ministers consider it vital to secure a reasonable revenue
support grant for next year so that the first year of the council tax does
not produce the sharp rises in bills that bedevilled the first year of the
poll tax.
One difficulty is that ministers still lack detailed information about the
tax base for the council tax, under which bills will be based largely on the
value of property in one of eight bands. The valuation exercise is not
expected to be completed until the end of next month at the earliest. Until
its results are available, ministers will have difficulty in knowing the
scale of the transitional relief scheme they will want to put in place.
A further complication is that the extra money to go to local authorities to
take account of their new duties in providing community care has yet to be
decided.
The government is still considering whether to prohibit councils from
spending the grant on other services.
Mr David Blunkett, Labour's local-government spokesman, said that the
Department of the Environment and the Treasury were 'locked in a battle
which will leave local government the loser'.
In the Commons, Tory and opposition MPs alike criticised the environment
secretary's decision to cap the 10 councils' spending.
Mr Howard said the move would mean reductions in the average poll tax in the
10 areas from Pounds 58 a payer in Basildon to Pounds 3 a payer in
Gloucester, benefiting 1.8m payers. The councils have 28 days to challenge
the decision.
Tory backbenchers were among those who warned that the limits on spending
would mean cuts in services.
The Labour-dominated Association of Metropolitan Authorities condemned the
capping arrangements. When provisional capping criteria were set, the
association said, that led almost all the other authorities to cut their
budgets to avoid being capped.
Mr Alan Howarth and Mr James Pawsey, Tory MPs for Stratford-on-Avon and for
Rugby and Kenilworth respectively, joined Labour colleagues for Warwickshire
in urging Mr Howard to relax the cap on Warwickshire.
Mr Pawsey warned of the risk of 'a strongly adverse effect on the services
being offered'.
Mr Howard said he would look carefully at any representations made to him
about the impact of standard spending assessments on capping, and that they
were continually kept under review.
