<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAY 92 / Pricing gap emerges in bank fees
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SOME HIGH street banks' charges to small-business customers are
substantially higher than their rivals', according to a survey of banking
business charges published by the consultancy Rochester Research.
The pricing gap is particularly wide between Lloyds and Midland, the two
banks locked in a takeover battle. Lloyds emerges as the most expensive bank
for small businesses and Midland the cheapest.
The survey was carried out in bank branches in Kent but its findings are
valid for the UK as a whole.
Rochester says some Lloyds small-business customers would save at least 20
per cent if they banked with Midland. It has forwarded a copy of its report
to the Office of Fair Trading, which is considering whether to refer Lloyds'
bid for Midland to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission.
Lloyds said yesterday it was unfair to compare its prices with Midland's
when predicting what customers of a merged bank might pay two years from
now.
'We have made it clear that the kind of cost savings which would then be
possible would clearly benefit the customer,' Lloyds said.
The bank declined to say why its charges were higher than those of the other
banks.
The survey says a small business with 80 transactions on its account each
month would find itself paying Pounds 39.50 a quarter more in charges if it
banked with Lloyds rather than Midland.
For a customer writing 60 cheques a month, paying six bills by standing
order and another six by direct debit, and receiving eight credits, Lloyds
would charge Pounds 187.50 compared with Midland's Pounds 147.90.
The charges of the other big clearers are closer to Midland than Lloyds. A
NatWest customer would pay Pounds 159.60 for identical services and a
Barclays customer Pounds 156.20.
Lloyds scores better than other banks with its Premier Interest Account, in
which businesses can hold funds.
Business Banking in the Medway Towns. Rochester Research, Readers, Millcroft
Road, Cliffe, Rochester. Pounds 5.
</TEXT>
