<TEXT>
THE SOCIAL Market Foundation, a think tank founded by supporters of the now
defunct Social Democratic party, will be relaunched today with the backing
of Mr David Sainsbury, one of Britain's wealthiest businessmen and a leading
supporter of the SDP until its demise.
The foundation will promote discussion of social policy in the framework of
a capitalist market economy.
The social market ideas espoused by Christian Democrats in Europe have
attracted increasing interest among Conservative thinkers such as Mr Chris
Patten.
The foundation's new board includes two Conservative MPs who entered the
Commons at the last election after serving as advisers to the prime
minister: Mrs Judith Chaplin, who was Mr Major's private secretary, and Mr
David Willetts, who was director of studies at the Centre for Policy
Studies, the Conservative think tank founded by Lord Joseph and Mrs
Thatcher.
Mr Andrew Tyrie, a former Treasury adviser who worked for Mr Nigel Lawson
and Mr Major, also joins the board.
The board includes a wide range of other interests, including Mr Samuel
Brittan, an assistant editor of the Financial Times, Professor John Kay of
the London Business School and Ms Sue Slipman of the National Council for
One-Parent Families.
Reflecting the drift of many leading lights of the SDP towards Mr John
Major's Conservative party, the foundation will be chaired by Lord
Skidelsky, an SDP life peer who has recently taken the Conservative whip in
the Lords.
