<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAY 92 / Approach to debts criticised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUILDING societies, utilities and local authorities are exacerbating
consumer debt troubles by their heavy-handed and inflexible approach,
according to the National Consumer Council.
In its annual survey of advice centres, the government-funded council says
that difficulties over paying for essential services such as water, housing
and fuel form a high proportion of cases requiring help.
The troubles brought to advice agencies are often linked in cycles that are
difficult to break. For example, people who have difficulty in paying bills
may be asked for a deposit in advance, which they cannot afford.
The council points out that consumers on low incomes often have to pay more
for essential services such as gas and electricity.
Pre-payment meters, which are helpful to consumers on a limited income, are
more expensive than quarterly billing.
The National Consumer Council also blames suppliers and local authorities
for delays and errors that posed further obstacles to consumers. The
collection of the poll tax has been particularly difficult, with confusing
billing methods and unclear instructions.
The recession appears to be leading to a tightening-up on debt collection
procedures, according to the survey. The council gives a warning that lack
of understanding and inflexibility about renegotiating repayments often made
debt delays worse.
The council concludes that 'with a little patience, understanding and with
sensible budgeting, most consumer debts can be repaid'.
Advice Monitor. National Consumer Council, 20 Grosvenor Gardens, London SW1W
0DH. Free.
</TEXT>
