<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAY 92 / Earnings rise continues: Reasons for the upward surge in
wages - Average pay increases 7.5%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE upward 'blip' in UK average earnings, announced yesterday, can be
explained by various special factors but still puts into sobering
perspective the controversy over a 5.4 per cent pay offer to Germany's
public-sector workers.
Germany, of course, is paying for reunification. But the figures make clear
that Britain can afford no complacency over its pay-setting arrangements.
In spite of a sharp reduction in inflation and the new discipline that ERM
membership is supposed to impose on the manufacturing sector, UK
manufacturing earnings are rising faster than all but three OECD countries:
Portugal, Greece and Italy.
According to the government's own figures, UK manufacturing earnings in
March were rising at an underlying rate of 8.25 per cent. The latest
available figures for other large countries include 6.6 per cent in Germany,
4.3 per cent in France, 2.7 per cent in the US and 1.7 per cent in Japan.
The underlying rate of increase in average earnings for the economy as a
whole was 7.5 per cent in March, more than 3 percentage points above
inflation. That is the same rate as February after an upward revision of
that month from 7.25 per cent to 7.5 per cent.
That figure disguises a jump of more than 10 per cent in earnings in many
sectors between February and March. There are two main reasons for that. One
is that many companies paid bonuses in March, earlier than usual, to save
their better-paid employees from the effects of a possible Labour
government's tax increases.
The other is that some workers will have received two pay rises in the 12
months to March. In March last year, when inflation was 8.24 per cent but
heading down quite rapidly, employers were trying to postpone pay
settlements. This year inflation is relatively stable, and is even expected
to rise slightly, so employers have been settling promptly.
Apart from those 'special factors', it should be remembered that average
earnings represent pay increases over a 12-month period, so the current
figure still includes pay rises from the middle of last year when inflation
was considerably higher.
Nevertheless, employers and the government have been expecting average
earnings to fall significantly, along with inflation, for nearly a year,
without any luck. Average earnings were rising at a rate of 7.75 per cent in
July last year, only 0.25 per cent above the March figure.
Even more worrying, there are signs that pay settlements - which have been
falling more rapidly - may be hitting a floor between 4 per cent and 5 per
cent. Settlements are usually a percentage point or 2 below earnings
increases because they exclude bonuses and overtime pay.
The Confederation of British Industry is still reporting pay freezes for
companies in special difficulty. The CBI, however, said settlements in
manufacturing in the first quarter of this year rose from 4.2 per cent to
4.3 per cent.
Some pay analysts are speculating that average earnings may not fall below 7
per cent at all, in the present cycle, if the recovery does pick up in the
next few weeks. That would mean an increase in overtime and other bonuses.
This view is probably too pessimistic and the recent low settlements from
the banking sector suggest there is still downward pressure on pay.
Even so, the latest 'blip' certainly serves to highlight the fact that
Britain still has a pay difficulty both in the public sector - where
settlements are running at about the German level of 5.4 per cent - and in
the private sector.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 9
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-7888</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEOAZAFAFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920515
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAY 92 / Yorks businesses see signs of recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUSINESS in the Yorkshire area and Humberside is beginning to show signs of
recovery but prospects are still fragile, the region's Confederation of
British Industry council said yesterday. There have been signs of further
improvement since the regional trends survey was compiled.
Mr Peter Barker, chairman of the regional council, said the most recent
evidence was of domestic orders increasing for some companies and being at
least stable for the majority.
'If the indicators on output and orders strengthen over the coming months -
and if businesses maintain the pressure on costs which now appears to be
bearing fruit - we should be able to discern a turning point and the
beginning of the recovery,' Mr Barker added.
He said the process would be slow, with definite signs elusive for some
time. Confidence was crucial, but the general election had strengthened it.
CBI members do not, however, expect employment prospects to improve. The
region is likely to have Britain's smallest year-on-year decline by the end
of June, but that will still be 2.8 percentage points.
</TEXT>
