<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAY 92 / Johnson Matthey wins tax plea
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JOHNSON MATTHEY, the precious metals company, yesterday won its appeal
against the Inland Revenue to receive tax relief on Pounds 50m granted to it
for the rescue of Johnson Matthey Bankers, its former subsidiary, seven
years ago.
The Bank of England rescued the bank, which ran into difficulties on its
commercial loans business, by buying its shares for Pounds 1. The rescue was
conditional on a Pounds 50m cash injection from Johnson Matthey.
Five law lords unanimously upheld the company's argument that the Pounds 50m
was a 'revenue payment' and hence deductible for corporation tax purposes.
Lord Templeman said the payment was solely to enable Johnson Matthey to
continue trading, because its own platinum-trading business would have
collapsed if Johnson Matthey Bankers had closed.
The Pounds 50m was not paid to persuade the Bank of England to buy worthless
shares in the bank, but to persuade it to rescue it and allow Johnson
Matthey to survive. A payment to preserve an existing business was
attributable to revenue, the lords stated.
The Revenue had argued that the Pounds 50m was a 'capital payment' to enable
Johnson Matthey to get rid of a capital asset, and liable to tax.
</TEXT>
