<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAY 92 / Tighter tax rules on equity note payments
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LEGISLATION is to be introduced by the government which, with effect from
midnight last night, will prevent multinational companies avoiding liability
for UK tax on payments made under equity notes - perpetual debt instruments
where the loan is not repaid.
Mr Stephen Dorrell, financial secretary to the Treasury, said in the Commons
that the Finance Bill to be published on May 20 would include provisions to
prevent the exploitation of a recent ruling by the special tax commissioners
arising from a double taxation agreement.
They decided certain payments under equity notes were interest for tax
purposes. Mr Dorrell said the Inland Revenue was considering an appeal
against the ruling.
He also announced that new clauses to be introduced in the committee stage
of the bill to confirm the existing basis for taxing life assurance
companies.
They had been made necessary by the claims made by some companies that the
existing basis could not apply when a trading loss was incurred.
</TEXT>
