<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAY 92 / Lloyd's inquiry to end in mid-June
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR DAVID Walker will complete his inquiries into alleged malpractices at
Lloyd's of London by mid-June and will hand his report to the insurance
market's authorities on July 1.
That timetable emerged after a meeting yesterday between the Securities and
Investments Board chairman and three Conservative MPs. When Sir David was
appointed in February it was stated that he would take at least two months
to complete his task.
It has also emerged that a report into the loss-making Feltrim syndicates -
the first of a number of loss reviews being conducted by Lloyd's - will not
be ready until August. It had been expected that the investigations, which
are being co-ordinated by Sir Patrick Neill QC, would be ready earlier this
year.
Yesterday's meeting came as the government was accused by the Labour party
of mounting a cover-up of malpractice at Lloyd's in an attempt to protect
its 21-strong Commons majority.
Mr Peter Hain, Labour MP for Neath, called for a debate on the market's
troubles and said there was evidence that 'the Council of Lloyd's - in
discussion with the Department of Trade and Industry - was involved in an
attempt using institutional finance to bail out Lloyd's Names including
MPs'.
A DTI official said yesterday that he had 'absolutely no knowledge' of the
discussions referred to by Mr Hain.
Mr Paul Marland, Tory MP for Gloucestershire West and a Lloyd's Name, joined
Mr Hain in calling for a Commons debate on the ground that there was
increasing evidence that the market was breaching the Lloyd's Act.
Mr Marland expressed satisfaction with the meeting with Sir David, which he
had attended along with Sir Gerard Vaughan, Conservative MP for Reading
East, and Sir Michael Marshall, Tory MP for Arundel.
In a separate development, Lloyd's Names who benefited from the out-of-court
settlement in the Outhwaite case yesterday won another legal victory.
After a two-day hearing in the Commercial Court Mr Justice Saville ordered
Lloyd's to pay the Pounds 116m directly to the 987 Names party to the
settlement agreed in February.
Last month Lloyd's blocked direct payment of the settlement to Names by
insisting that money be paid to its premium trust funds - the funds into
which all underwriting money earned by Lloyd's underwriters is paid.
The complication arose because some Names who benefited from the Outhwaite
action are also members of loss-making syndicates - such as those managed by
the Feltrim and Gooda Walker agencies - and have outstanding liabilities
from those separate underwriting activities.
In the cases of those Names, Lloyd's intended to offset settlement monies
against these other liabilities.
Mr Anthony Boswood QC, representing the Names, said that the decision had
caused Names 'grievous financial hardship'. Lloyd's said it will not appeal.
</TEXT>
