<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAY 92 / ITV proposes to block re-runs by rival broadcasters
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NEW ITV network plans to buy rights to programmes for up to 15 years to
keep them out of the hands of rival broadcasters.
Mr Greg Dyke, chairman of the ITV Association and chief executive of London
Weekend Television, said yesterday that ITV wanted to buy the right to show
a programme three times over 10 years. There would also be an option for a
further five years.
'What we are trying to do is defend ITV and not find its programmes used
against it,' Mr Dyke said. He was speaking as ITV published the details of
the new centralised ITV network and the proposed contracts that will govern
programme commissioning and purchase in the future.
The new policy on buying rights is expected to be investigated by the Office
of Fair Trading in addition to its general responsibility under broadcasting
legislation to ensure the network arrangements are open and fair.
Mr Dyke said the ITV companies did not want to fall into the trap of
networks in the US, where re-runs of their old programmes shown by
independent stations and on cable television had eaten into audience share.
The ITV move to control rights and often keep programmes on the shelf for
years will undermine hopes that a secondary market will develop in the UK
for the rights to programmes already shown once on national commercial
television.
The strategy will prove controversial with independent producers, who want
to keep as many of the secondary rights in programmes as possible to sell in
other markets.
Mr Dyke said yesterday ITV would if necessary be prepared to pay more to
guarantee full rights to programmes, and added that it was very much a
buyers' market for programmes. ITV might end up 'buying less or not buying
at all' from producers who did not want to sell 10-year rights.
If approved by the OFT, the new policy, which would take effect from
September next year, might have a significant effect on Channel 4, which has
scored significant ratings successes with repeats of popular ITV programmes
such as the detective series Inspector Morse.
In future, the ITV network will be put together by a centralised system run
by a chief executive and a network director, who will be spending an annual
programme budget of about Pounds 500m.
</TEXT>
