<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAY 92 / Phone codes may cost industry Pounds 3bn: Telecom managers
association urges Oftel to delay for at least two years proposals on extra
digit for numbers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGO DIXON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CHANGES planned for telephone codes may cost industry more than Pounds 3bn,
according to an organisation representing large telephone users.
The Telecommunications Managers Association (TMA) has urged Oftel, the
telecommunications regulator, to shelve proposals to introduce new codes in
spring 1994 for at least two years.
Oftel announced last September that all codes would have the digit '1'
inserted after the initial '0' to cope with a shortage of telephone numbers,
caused by growing competition in telephone services and increased demand for
numbers.
For example, Birmingham's 021 code would become 0121 while London's 071 and
081 would become 0171 and 0181.
Its Pounds 3bn estimate of the cost takes into account modifying - or even
scrapping - equipment, reprinting stationery and advertising the change.
The TMA's objections have already stopped Oftel from giving final approval
for the code change - Oftel's internal estimates put the cost at only Pounds
200m. A national campaign to alert customers, due to have started at the
beginning of this month, was postponed at short notice.
The delay is worrying parts of the industry. BT, Britain's largest
telecommunications group, and the Telecommunications Users' Association,
another user group, believe any further delay will give customers even less
time to prepare for the change.
In addition to the high cost of the planned change, the TMA has told Oftel
that it would not even meet the difficulty of a shortage of numbers and
that, in a few years, there would be further number changes and yet more
disruption.
Instead of a wholesale change to codes, it has proposed a stopgap scheme to
buy time while Oftel examines whether there is a better long-term solution.
The TMA's idea would involve taking codes from rural communities, where
there are few users, and reallocating them to the areas with a shortage.
Its fears of further disruption are confirmed by the fact that BT has
recently put a proposal to Oftel that would involve more than a million
customers in five cities changing both their codes and numbers.
Numbers in Leeds, Nottingham, Bristol, Sheffield and Leicester would change
from six digits to seven, while their current codes would be replaced with
prefixes from the series '0111', '0112', '0113'.
</TEXT>
