<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAY 92 / Accord on BCCI attacked by senator in US
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE proposed Dollars 1.7bn settlement for creditors of the collapsed Bank of
Credit and Commerce International (BCCI) came under fire in the US senate
yesterday as Senator John Kerry, who has been investigating BCCI, described
the proposal as 'unfair'.
He made his remarks to Mr Brian Smouha, the BCCI liquidator, who gave his
first Congressional testimony on the BCCI affair.
The senator, at a foreign affairs sub-committee hearing, called into
question the settlement - by which the government of Abu Dhabi would pay
BCCI creditors between 30 and 40 cents in the dollar - because creditors
would be forced to waive their rights to bring any legal action against Abu
Dhabi. The government there is the BCCI majority shareholder.
Mr Kerry also criticised Abu Dhabi for its failure thus far to supply US
authorities with key BCCI documents and with former executives of the bank
being held under house arrest.
The senator said the BCCI creditors 'deserve to know that, if there are deep
pockets that fleece them, they have the right to take action.' He added:
'You have to understand who is responsible for the BCCI affair before you
strike some deal that wipes this all away. I would call this an unfair trade
practice.'
Mr Ahmed al Sayegh, a director of the Abu Dhabi National Oil Company and a
member of the government's BCCI working group, said Abu Dhabi had no
involvement in the frauds perpetrated by BCCI. He added that Abu Dhabi is in
talks with the US Justice Department over the possibility of making
available BCCI documents and witnesses now in Abu Dhabi.
Mr al Sayegh also criticised former BCCI auditors Price Waterhouse as
'negligent', and said the accounting firm 'should accept responsibility for
their failure to uncover the true position year after year.'
Mr Smouha responded to Mr Kerry's criticism by saying that what he had
sought was to 'negotiate a commercial solution.'
The settlement, which will be reviewed at a UK high court hearing in June,
will need to be approved by BCCI creditors and courts in the UK, Luxembourg
and the Cayman Islands.
A former top prosecutor claimed in earlier testimony to the sub-committee he
had been impeded last year by the Justice Department in his efforts to
obtain documents and bring indictments against BCCI.
Mr Dexter Lehtinen, US attorney in Miami until four months ago, complained
that, despite numerous written requests to Washington, the department
declined to give him permission to enforce subpoenas demanding crucial BCCI
documents about the bank's Luxembourg and other non-US operations.
Anger at MP's claim, Page 10
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
