<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAY 92 / Serb bid to evade EC freeze on assets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY and LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Serbian authorities have been withdrawing assets from western banks, and
from banks in Belgrade, the Serbian capital, in an attempt to circumvent
further European Community sanctions.
The EC has not yet drawn up any concrete measures to seize such assets, nor
have central bankers received warnings or instructions to prepare for such a
possibility. Nevertheless, more than Dollars 1.5bn has been taken out of
Belgrade over the past six months, while assets held in the UK had
decreased, western bankers and diplomats said yesterday.
In Sarajevo, the Bosnian capital, the Presidency building came under attack
yesterday, with shells exploding nearby every 20 seconds, according to Mr
Hajrudim Somun, an official inside. He said the Interior Ministry had also
been hit.
The largely Moslem Bosnian Territorial Defence Forces yesterday made a
desperate attempt to break a siege which Serb militia, backed by the
Yugoslav army, have imposed on the city for the past two weeks.
General Lew Mckenzie, a Canadian commander of the UN peacekeeping forces,
said Moslem forces tried to break out of the encirclement but the federal
army 'massively retaliated'.
Faced with severe shortage of food and medical supplies, the Bosnia militia
yesterday were forced to open up a route out of the city, thus ending the
fragile ceasefire announced by the Serb militia earlier in the week.
Eye-witnesses said Bosnian militiamen battled against Serb irregulars
between blocks of flats. One witness said: 'It is the worst street fighting
ever.'
Several mortar shells hit the Rainbow Hotel, which houses some 250 United
Nations peacekeepers, wounding a member of the UN staff and setting ablaze
12 vehicles.
Yugoslavia's assets abroad, not including assets held overseas by Slovene or
Croatian banks, totalled Dollars 2.9bn up to December 1991.
Claims on Yugoslav hard currency deposits held in the UK totalled Dollars
685m by the end of December - Dollars 582m held in foreign currencies, and
the remainder in sterling. This represents a sharp fall from the previous
quarter, when all Yugoslav assets in the UK totalled Dollars 1.1bn.
The decline is partly related to the withdrawal of these assets, as well as
moves by Slovenia and Croatia, who declared their independence last June, to
protect their assets against Serbia, and the Serb-dominated National Bank of
Yugoslavia.
EC diplomats said yesterday further sanctions against Serbia were discussed
by foreign ministers last Monday. There was no decision to freeze Serbia's
assets, a British official said.
Moves by the EC and the US to isolate Serbia have mounted over the past week
in an attempt to apply pressure on Serbia's President Slobodan Milosevic to
stop the fighting in the war-torn former Yugoslav republic of
Bosnia-Hercegovina. Serbia, and Montenegro, its ally, declared themselves
the successor to the former Yugoslavia, but the EC, the US and the countries
of eastern Europe have not recognised the new Yugoslavia.
The EC withdrew its ambassadors from Belgrade on Monday and will exclude
Yugoslavia from any discussions about Bosnia at the Conference on Security
and Co-operation in Europe.
</TEXT>
