<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAY 92 / Insurance directive approved
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE WAY was cleared yesterday for European Community composite insurers  -
which combine life and non-life insurance operations - to open branches
throughout the EC after July 1994.
EC ministers agreed the third life assurance directive, although formal
approval will have to wait until it has been passed by the European
parliament. Earlier EC legislation restricted the rights of composite
insurers - mainly British, Italian and Belgian - to establish themselves in
other states.
Member states such as Spain, Ireland and the Netherlands, which had wanted
to maintain restrictions, yesterday dropped their objections. Restrictions
on new composite insurers will remain, subject to a later review of the
legislation: new composites wanting to open branches in third countries will
only be able to sell life and health insurance.
Insurance networks will be controlled by supervisory authorities in the
companies' home states. However, until the end of 1995 in Spain and
Portugal, and the end of 1998 in Greece, those national authorities will
continue to exercise local control over foreign insurers' subsidiaries,
according to the directive's rules.
</TEXT>
