<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAY 92 / Britain gets its way on frontier declaration
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN yesterday persuaded its EC partners to water down a declaration on
the abolition of frontier controls, so as not to prejudice its hard-line
position on the preservation of border-checks on people.
The declaration by internal market ministers outlines the measures which
need to be taken to remove barriers to the free movement of goods after
January 1, 1993.
But Mr Richard Needham, British minister for trade, insisted that the draft
declaration should be amended to make clear the UK's opposition to the
removal of checks on people crossing internal EC frontiers. For example, the
text no longer refers to the member states giving priority to the abolition
of 'all border controls'.
It is the second time this week that the UK has made clear its determination
to preserve checks, against the wishes of the European Commission. On
Monday, Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary, reiterated the country's
determination to maintain controls over people. The Commission is
threatening the UK with legal action if it does not remove border checks on
travellers entering from other Community states.
</TEXT>
