<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAY 92 / Money Markets: Rates soften slightly
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MONEY MARKET rates softened slightly yesterday after the Bank of England
forecast a smaller shortage than had been expected in the discount market.
But the market's underlying view remained bearish about a cut in base rates
in the near future.
The cost of 1-month and 2-month money softened slightly after the Bank
forecast a shortage of only Pounds 500m in the morning. As the shortage was
easily taken up, 1-month money ended the day at 10 1/16 per cent, down from
10 1/16 - 1/32 per cent the day before.
2-month money also ended at 10 1/16 from a previous close of 10 3/32 per
cent.
One trader said that these reductions were purely technical. He said that
the overnight rate had dipped as low as 8 1/2 per cent because of the high
liquidity in the system and, as a result, traders were more willing to lend
at longer rates.
The market's underlying pessimism about a rate cut was reinforced by poor UK
economic figures. These showed that unemployment grew by a bigger than
expected 42,600 in April to reach 2,695,300. Average earnings in March also
increased by 7.5 per cent, the same as the February figure which was revised
up from the original estimate of 7.25%.
There was disappointment at sterling's performance on foreign currency
markets with the pound trickling away from its best levels and closing at
DM2.9375. Sterling futures reflected those poor figures. The September
contract ended the day at 90.24, eight ticks down on the previous close, and
implying that base rates in September will be at 9.76 per cent. The December
contract ended at 90.49, down ten ticks, and implying that base rate at the
end of the year will be 9.51 per cent.
The discount market had a very quiet day. In the morning, the Bank of
England forecast a shortage of Pounds 550m. The forecast was later revised
to a shortage of around Pounds 500m. The Bank then purchased Pounds 500m of
Band-1 Bank bills at 9 7/8 per cent. The shortage was later revised to
around Pounds 600m before taking account of the morning operations. The Bank
then purchased Pounds 109m of Band-1 bank bills at 9 7/8 per cent.
German call money rates eased yesterday to just below 9.60 per cent for the
first time in two months after the Bundesbank added liquidity to the market
on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
