<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAY 92 / MPs censure PSA Services
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE management of PSA Services, the government agency that carries out
building works for the Civil Service, has been censured by the Commons
public accounts committee.
The agency - which is due for privatisation later this year - had to write
off invoices worth Pounds 65.6m in its 1990-91 accounts because customers
would not accept them. That followed difficulties in implementing new
systems which the PAC describes as 'a most serious matter'.
The snags arose when government departments became free to employ
private-sector companies for building works on April 1 1990. PSA Services
introduced new financial systems to cost and invoice work at the same time
as preparing for privatisation.
Difficulties in implementing the new systems and inadequacies in the
underlying records led to errors on customers' invoices. Payment on those
invoices was delayed or withheld and the Pounds 65.6m shortfall was met from
public funds.
The PAC notes PSA Services' assurances that there is no evidence of
impropriety, but says the breakdown in controls created an environment 'in
which impropriety could flourish and be difficult to detect'.
PSA Services Accounts 1990-91. HC208. HMSO. Pounds 8.75.
</TEXT>
