<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAY 92 / Council contracts out tax collecting
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COLLECTION of local taxes and the payment of benefits is to be contracted
out to the private sector by East Cambridgeshire district council, in the
first successful competitive tender for a local-authority white-collar
function.
The council sought competitive tenders for the collection of poll tax and
business rates - and council tax when that is introduced next year  - and
the payment of housing benefit and poll tax benefit. The contract, worth
Pounds 3.5m over five years, has been awarded to Capita Group from this
month.
The council's 23 revenue collection and benefits staff have chosen to
transfer to Capita, and the service will continue to be provided from the
existing premises. If service targets are exceeded, Capita will be paid a
performance bonus. If standards are not met, their fee will be reduced.
Capita already works under contract for more than 20 local councils in
chasing up poll tax payments by phone, but this is the first contract
involving the entire revenue collection and benefits payment service.
Competitive tendering is due to be extended to a wide range of council
professional and technical services under legislation passed in the last
parliament. Details of the scope of such contracting out and the timetable
are due to be announced soon, after officials have considered more than 500
submissions on a consultative paper issued last autumn.
</TEXT>
