<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAY 92 / Commercial vehicle output surges: April car output down on
last year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CAR PRODUCTION in the UK was 2.3 per cent lower last month than in April
last year but output of commercial vehicles was sharply higher, continuing
the strong recovery started late last year.
Car output in April, at 108,641, fell from 111,138 in the same month a year
ago, according to figures released by the Society of Motor Manufacturers and
Traders and the Central Statistical Office.
In the first four months of this year, car production was 1.2 per cent lower
at 451,959 compared with 457,301 in the same period last year.
Output for the domestic market has strengthened and rose year-on-year by
13.8 per cent in the first four months to 263,962. That was offset by
falling production for export markets, which were 16.6 per cent lower at
187,997.
On a seasonally adjusted basis, car output in the past six months was 1 per
cent higher than in the previous six months but 6 per cent lower than in the
same period a year ago.
Commercial vehicle production of 22,555 in April was 24.6 per cent higher
than in the same month a year ago. Output in the first four months was 17.5
per cent higher, at 89,399, compared with 76,063 in the same period last
year.
Output of commercial vehicles has been helped by an increase in output of
small vans by Ford, which started producing its new Courier high-roof Fiesta
van range at Dagenham late last year.
UK sales have fallen for 31 consecutive months year-on-year and the domestic
commercial vehicle market remains depressed, but the rise in output this
year has been supported by a big jump in exports.
</TEXT>
