<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAY 92 / Survey: FT Traveller, Genoa (10) - Part of the fabric of
life / Wine, Vine cultivation on the steep and windy slopes of the Cinque
Terre requires strong leg muscles and a head for heights
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'YOU NEED a passion to do it. Many only keep up the tradition out of respect
for their parents.' So Mr Nello Capris, a leading Genoese wine expert,
describes the task of vine cultivation in the wild Cinque Terre, where
strong leg muscles and a head for heights are as much pre-requisites for
success as green fingers with the grape.
Producing wine on the steep and windy slopes of the Cinque Terre, the five
small villages just north of La Spezia, around 75 miles south of Genoa, is,
says Mr Capris, 'a heroic task'. The narrow terraces perched along the
near-vertical hillsides plunging down towards the sea offer little scope for
mechanisation. Much of the work, including the carrying, is still done by
hand.
'No one could keep a family solely on the income from growing wine,' he
explains. 'Growing vines is now virtually all part-time work, either done as
a second job or left to those who have already retired.'
In spite of the immense difficulties, the wine business has not eroded, like
many of the harsh hillsides which face the sea. For growing wine is part of
the fabric of life in a region which, in spite of its immense tourist
appeal, still depends largely on traditional sources of income for its
livelihood. Without their vineyards, the five villages which make up the
remote Cinque Terre would still be magnets for visitors on account of their
ragged beauty and commanding views, but part of their magic would be lost.
It is largely because of tourism that the two white wines of the Cinque
Terre - Cinqueterre and Sciaccetra - are among the best known of all
Liguria's produce, in spite of the relatively small quantities produced
visitors buy the fruity Cinqueterre or, to a much lesser extent, sweet
Sciaccetra dessert wine, in much the same decorative three-bottle cardboard
packs as are found in other locations where tourism and wine-growing go hand
in hand like Rudesheim on the Rhine or the villages south of Strasbourg in
Alsace.
Like their counterparts elsewhere in Italy, the growers of the Cinque Terre
have recently woken up to the possibilities of 'agro-tourism'. Largely
united in the Co-operativa Agricoltora Cinqueterre, the local growers are
now starting to convert some of the small abandoned shacks dotted around the
hillsides into basic accommodation for visitors.
Tourists searching for five-star luxury should look elsewhere. But the
provision of electricity and running water to the huts, traditionally used
for storage and even temporary accommodation for workers on outlying
vineyards, could appeal to the thousands of walkers and ramblers who descend
on the region each year. Meanwhile, for the local economy, converting the
huts could persuade visitors to stay for longer than the usual day-trip,
which contributes little revenue to the community.
By combining their interests, the members of the co-operative have helped to
maintain an industry marked by a steady decline in the past. 'The problem is
that the population is getting older, and the young people are drifting
away. You can't change it,' says Mr Capris. Economic pressures make it
increasingly difficult for younger members of wine-growing families to
maintain the family business.
The co-operative may not be able completely to reverse the tide, but it is
at least trying to make the best of what is left. Agreement has already been
reached with some local growers to give the co-operative the right of first
refusal over their land should they decide to go out of business.
Meanwhile, the co-operative, which comprises around three quarters of the
local producers, has also strengthened their lobbying powers when it comes
to outside bodies. Most recently, they secured funding from the European
Community to install around 30 narrow mini-railways up some of the steepest
local slopes to make the task of transporting grapes after harvest less of
an endurance test.
The Cinque Terre is the best known of the wine-growing areas of Liguria, but
the region as a whole is as unfamiliar to most Italians as it is to
foreigners on account of its limited output. Producing only around 300,000
hectolitres of wine a year, Liguria is one of Italy's smallest wine-growing
zones, representing barely 0.5 per cent of national output.
However, it is slowly gaining ground, reckons Mr Capris. Quality has
improved, especially over the past decade. 'Ligurian wine was not always
produced that professionally. It didn't always look good, nor keep well. Now
we've managed to convince more top restaurants to take local wines, and
they've been pleased with their choice,' he says.
Like much in Liguria, the wine-growing region forms two sides of an arc with
Genoa at its head. Although most of the wine business is concentrated in two
areas around Albenga to the west and La Spezia to the east, even Genoa
itself has some wines.
The city's wines do not merit being classed among Italy's top-drawer
'Denominazione di Origine Controllata' (DOC) rating. However, they are
ranked one notch down the scale as table wines coming from a strictly
defined geographical region.
Even that may seem surprising to those who remember that the local white
Valpolcevera was known for decades as the standard tipple for Genoa's
thirsty dockers. 'Mornings would start with a swig of wine and continue in
much the same way all day,' jokes Mr Capris.
However, change is now on the cards for Genoa's local wine, as well as for
Verminto di Ne and Bianco di Verici, two other local whites. Subject to a
variety of approvals, including the European Commission, the local wines
will eventually all be called Golfo del Tigullio, a name harking back to the
inhabitants of the Gulf of Genoa in pre-Roman times.
While wines from around La Spezia, including the Cinque Terre and the nearby
Colli di Luni stretching south to Tuscany, account for around half Liguria's
output, wines from areas to the west of Genoa form much of the remainder.
The Rossesse di Dolceacqua DOC, produced in about five villages around
Ventimiglia on the border with France, accounts for a fraction of that
total. The red wines, similar to the well-known Barolo from Piedmont to the
north, have been produced for centuries and are strong and mature quickly.
But rather than seeking out obscure growths, visitors to Genoa would do well
to remember the names of Pigato and Vermintino, two of Liguria's most
commonly found wines, which make up the bulk of the output from the western
Riviera. The two whites are 'classic Ligurian wines', says Mr Capris, light
and fruity. 'Some experts even claim to detect a a hint of salt, brought in
from the sea,' he adds, somewhat sceptically. Both wines, along with the
less familiar red Rossesse, form part of the 'Riviera Ligure di Ponente'
DOC, which is concentrated around Albenga.
Surprisingly, little or no wine is produced from the shady valleys in the
hinterland behind Genoa and the other coastal resorts. The relatively high
altitude of the Apennines and the cool temperatures are the main culprits,
although depopulation has also played a role. 'There were few people there
before, and there are even fewer now,' notes Mr Capris.
As in parts of the Cinque Terre, many smaller or less accessible vineyards
have been abandoned or sold. The Italian legal system, which requires an
estate to be split between all the heirs, has not helped, as holdings have
been divided into increasingly small fractions over the years. And Liguria's
harsh geography, with a lack of land which can be cultivated easily, has
encouraged new owners to convert fields once devoted to wine to other, more
profitable or essential, uses.
Although a law now exists to give tax advantages to farmers amalgamating
wine-growing plots, human interests often come into play. 'Ligurians are
very individualistic. Even setting up the Cinque Terre co-operative was a
herculean task,' says Mr Capris.
The economic pressures on growers are particularly evident around Albenga,
one of the few parts of Liguria where the coastal strip broadens out from a
thin belt, sandwiched between the mountains and the sea, into a sizeable
area of flat, easily arable land. Here, the competition is from
horticulture, which is already dominant further to the west. Growing flowers
is not only less labour intensive and more easily mechanised, but more
profitable, too.
Such factors mean Ligurian wine will always remain a speciality in Italy.
The difficulties of growing vines in the region are reflected in the price
of grapes, which, at around L2,000 a kilo, is almost three times as high as
in neighbouring Piedmont. Those costs are naturally mirrored in the price of
a bottle of Ligurian wine, which at around L8,000-L10,000, is above the
Italian average.
However, local growers are not despondent, particularly in view of the
greater recognition they have received over the past 10-15 years. And for
visitors who want to impress their Ligurian hosts, a gift of Sciaccetra,
which weighs in at around L50,000-60,000 a bottle, should go down
particularly well.
</TEXT>
