<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAY 92 / Survey: FT Traveller, Genoa (9) - Football's year to
remember / Sports, The Columbus festivities in 1992 include international
cycling, water polo, athletics, roller skating and sailing events
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARBARA LIGHTWOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN A COUNTRY totally dominated by football, Genoa is certainly no exception.
It was here in 1893 that a group of British subjects founded the first
Italian sporting society, the Genoa Cricket and Athletic Club, at the local
British consulate.
The cricket and athletics gave way to association football, and today the
city is divided between Genoa, the club that descended from the society of
yore, and Sampdoria, the side that brought home the Italian championship
title last season.
The title was captured by a team revitalised through the investments of
chairman Paolo Mantovani, who in just over 10 years pushed what had long
been considered 'Genoa's other team' to success against clubs backed by the
largest business empires in Italy (Agnelli's Juventus and Berlusconi's
Milan).
Whether sustained by a prestigious past or more recent successes, the
Genovese are first and foremost grandstand 'supporters': impassioned,
sometimes even sombre, always extremely fair - and rather satisfied with
results in 1992.
For the first time in their history, both teams have been involved at the
highest levels of international tournaments at the same time.
While the Genoa club missed out on the UEFA cup, it had the consolation
prize of playing in the semi-finals and achieving two historic victories
against Liverpool.
Meanwhile, the Sampdoria fans are busy organising their expedition to
Wembley, where their team will battle Barcelona for the Champions' Cup.
But the 1992 sporting year in Genoa will not be dominated by football: the
Columbus festivities include international cycling, water polo, track and
field and sailing events.
The Genovese have become aware that the Columbus festival offers an
opportunity for relaunching the city, and that sport can encourage the
process. So they have partly overcome their traditional reluctance to embark
on relatively risky investments. In the case of sports, the financial
caution of public authorities and private sponsors even went so far as to
penalise activities in which the city was once outstanding.
One of the chronic problems afflicting sports in Genoa is a lack of
management, facilities and space in which to build arenas and playing
fields. The city is now trying to remedy this problem which, for example,
resulted in the loss of a basketball team, Emerson, and the shift of the
water polo centre to the nearby Riviera, which has better facilities.
Other lost opportunities include a world swimming tournament, the baseball
World Cup and international boxing, motorcycling and sailing events, and
probably the finals of the volleyball World League.
So, while the Genovese await new facilities (which will include a new sports
arena and the new 'Sciorba' multisports centre), they are seeking to make
the most of what they have.
In the events that did not escape in 1992 they have demonstrated a new
enthusiasm: speed of execution and managerial capacity on the part of
organisers and a great deal of interest from the public.
The big sport in February was track and field, first with the CUS Genoa
Trophy, which attracted international athletes such as Leroy Burrell, the
American runner, and Jamaica's Merlene Ottey, both favourites to win sprint
gold medals at this year's Olympic Games to be held in Barcelona.
This was followed by the three days of the European Indoor Championships, a
testing ground for the Olympics, marked by the first participation of teams
from Lithuania, Estonia and Latvia.
The latest event, following the World Under-20 Fencing Championships last
month, was the departure of the Columbus '92 Quincentenary Grand Regatta,
with the participation of Spain, Portugal, the UK, Puerto Rico, the United
States and, of course, Italy.
One hundred and fifty veteran ships, including 25 school vessels, will
undertake six legs from Genoa to Liverpool, where they are due to arrive
between August 13 and 16 after covering 9,300 miles of ocean sailed in the
name of Columbus.
One of the organisers of the regatta is the Yacht Club Italiano of Genoa,
one of the world's prestigious sailing clubs, which for more than a century
has been helping to uphold the city's maritime tradition.
Founded in 1879 with the patronage of King Humbert I, the YCI has provided
outstanding figures in world sailing, such as the late Beppe Croce, who
succeeded Peter Scott as president of the International Yacht Racing Union.
With Giovanni Novi at its helm today, the club boasts around 1,000 members
who were able to meet the rigorous membership requirements. The most
illustrious include leading businessmen such as Raul Gardini, Carlo Bonomi,
Gianni Verasi and Giorgio Falck.
Genoa will also be the scene of an international cycling competition this
year: in addition to the Apennine Tour earlier this month, the Tour of Italy
will once again start out from Genoa (May 22-25) after a 12-year absence,
with the first pink jersey awarded in the name of Columbus.
The APT tennis tour will be in Genoa from June 15 to 21 with the IP cup (won
last year by Carl-Uwe Steeb). Thereafter the city will host the World
Rollerskating championships (September 3-6), thanks in part to Ingrid Van
Marie, the multiple international title winner and Genovese by adoption.
Young athletes, ranging from six to 14 years of age, will take part in the
national finals of the Youth Games from October 4 to 10; there are 8,000
Italian participants (plus 1,000 Spanish and American guests), who will
compete in events scattered throughout the Ligurian region. The final awards
ceremony of the Games will be held in the new Expo area inside the port.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
