<DOCNO>FT922-8061</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEOAZAAGFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920515
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAY 92 / Survey: FT Traveller, Genoa (7) - An annual Mecca for
sailors / Fairs, The October Boat Show is one of the biggest events of its
kind in the world and attracts around 350,000 visitors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PERCHED on the delta of the river Bisagno on land rescued from the sea,
Genoa's fair symbolises much about its host city.
With the Mediterranean its immediate neighbour and the city centre just
minutes away on foot, the fair highlights the advantages and disadvantages
of Genoa's geography. For while the setting may be unbeatable, the narrow
site offers little scope for expansion.
In spite of its limitations, the fair comes into its own for 10 days each
October, when it hosts the International Boat Show. One of the biggest
events of its kind in the world, the Boat Show attracts around 350,000
visitors, more than half from outside Genoa and around 20,000 from abroad.
The figures for the Boat Show are impressive, with more than 800 exhibitors
and 1,500 boats on display in every corner of the narrow site. The biggest
boats are reserved for Hall B, which, with its four-storey height, can take
big sailing boats up to 32 metres long, masts and all.
Bigger vessels, which are also seen regularly in Genoa, have to stay on the
water in the specially-built marina used as additional exhibition space
during the show and rented out to local sailors for the rest of the year.
Having the marina at hand means Genoa can offer much the same amount of
exhibition space as its bigger international rivals.
Although the boat shows at Dusseldorf and Miami are about the same size, no
other exhibition of its kind offers the same combination of sophisticated
interior facilities and external possibilities on the water, says Mr
Giuseppino Roberto, the fair's secretary-general.
The Boat Show, which will celebrate its 33rd anniversary this year, used to
be held in February until it was shifted to October in 1972. 'The choice of
October was very fortunate. Although it is at the end of the season, it is
still very much late summer in Liguria, meaning the weather is very pleasant
and people want to come to look at boats,' says Mr Roberto.
He is less communicative about the competitive factors which may also have
forced the change. Boat shows have become big business in rich European
countries and in the US. Apart from Dusseldorf and Miami, Genoa also faces
rivals in London, Paris, Barcelona and a number of the Scandinavian
countries.
The decision to hold a boat show in Genoa reflects the thinking behind the
creation of the fair in the mid-1950s. Building started in 1959, and the
first Boat Show opened in 1962. 'With Genoa's traditions as a seaport, the
original idea was to create a big event concentrating on communications,
especially on a cultural level,' Mr Roberto recalls. However, early
'communications fairs' showed the concept had little commercial validity, he
admits.
It was a different story for the Boat Show, which gave Liguria's
recreational shipbuilders a chance to show off their wares and the region's
sea-loving public the opportunity to gawp and, sometimes, to buy.
But while exhibiting boats turned out to be a swift success, the fair had to
dream up other commercially-viable attractions. Many have fallen by the
wayside, but two - Tecnhotel and Euroflora - have become established events.
The first is devoted to the hotel business, while the second, held every
five years, is a huge horticultural extravaganza. The success of both fairs
illustrates the importance of presenting shows which have some local roots.
With its huge tourist business and thousands of hotels along the Riviera,
Tecnhotel fulfils a clear need. Likewise, staging Euroflora, which pulls in
around 700,000 visitors for its 10-day run, is appropriate for Genoa given
the Riviera's role as Italy's horticultural heart.
Tecnhotel, which now has an additional fair on contract furnishing tacked
on, began in 1965, while the first Euroflora was held in 1966. The most
recent show, held last year, understandably had a Christopher Columbus
theme, with the focus on the plants and flowers of north America, says Mr
Roberto.
While the Boat Show, Tecnhotel and Euroflora are Genoa's three big
international events, the city also holds a variety of other, more
specialised, fairs. Riabitat, held every two years, concentrates on the
businesses of restoring and modernising buildings. Restoration often
features as a side event at many big international building fairs. But no
other city has an event devoted solely to the subject, says Mr Roberto.
'It's particularly appropriate if you think of Italy, with its historic city
centres, where there is a culture of building which must last for
centuries.'
More recently, the fair has come up with Auto Story, a specialist exhibition
of prestige and veteran cars, now in its second year. The fair has had a
good reception from the public and car dealers, he says.
But in a business noted for its competition, both internationally and
between fairs in their own countries, Genoa will have to carry on thinking
up new ideas if it is not to rely exclusively on its three big international
events, one of which, after all, is only held twice a decade. The fair
recognises, but may not have yet met, the challenge.
Domestically, both the Milan and Bologna fairs are appreciably bigger in
terms of size and prestige. Genoa ranks roughly on a par with cities such as
Turin, Verona and Bari, all of which have around the same amount of space
available and which all hold at least one event of international importance,
as well as many other shows of more local interest.
But in some ways, the priority for Genova is to hold its own, implies Mr
Roberto. Surprisingly, the fair is not seen as a potential profit-maker for
the city. Rather, he takes pride in the fact that it has generally managed
to balance its books. Small surpluses in the past 10 years have been used to
improve the facilities, with L12bn being spent on creating the marina and
L8bn on modernising the congress centre.
However, the L15bn investment now needed to upgrade facilities and improve
essential services such as electricity and water will have to come from
outside sources. 'The big profits come from big events which draw over
50,000 visitors. We don't have many of those,' Mr Roberto admits. 'Our aim
is more towards providing an overall benefit towards the city.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XI
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-8062</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEOAZAAFFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920515
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAY 92 / Survey: FT Traveller, Genoa (6) - Symbol of lost
opportunities / The Harbour, The flag of privatisation is now flying highest
at the port - surprisingly, for a former centre of hard-left politics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN A CITY renowned for its reserve, nothing provokes an argument faster than
the port. For its critics, the port symbolises decades of politicised
management, bungling and lost opportunities, notably in failing to come to
terms with containerisation.
Added to that has been a reluctance to confront restrictive labour
practices, which led to high costs and an inevitable downward spiral of
lower competitiveness and steady decline. From 51m tonnes in 1980, cargo
handled fell to 44m last year, including oil and related products, which
comprised more than half the overall tonnage in 1991. Meanwhile, the number
of dockers has dropped to just over 1,000 from more than 7,000 15 years ago.
To some extent, the argument has already been won. Even the port's
management, concentrated in the 13th Century Palazzo San Giorgio, admits
Genoa must adapt or die. What they add is that change is already well under
way.
Surprisingly for a former centre of hard-left politics, it is at the port
that the flag of privatisation is now flying highest. Under plans originally
drawn up in 1984, and subsequently refined, the Port Authority is bringing
in private companies as partners in a number of joint ventures within the
traditional port area. Meanwhile, at Voltri, six miles to the west, a L180bn
scheme is under way to build the biggest container terminal in the
Mediterranean, with the Port Authority as only a junior partner to private
sector capital.
The Port Authority has singled out seven activities in the old port in which
it wants private-sector participation, explains Mr Rinaldo Magnani, a former
dock worker and ex-president of Liguria, who is now its chairman.
The terminals include fruit, general bulk cargoes, fertilisers and roll-on
roll-off transport. The most likely private sector shareholders will be the
big companies already using the facilities, he explains. So far, Coeclerici,
a leading trader and fruit importer, has joined forces with the Port
Authority at the fruit terminal, Ferruzzi and two other private companies
are participating on the ro-ro side, while the Camelli group has come in for
bulk cargoes. 'We're trying out a concept which could eventually be applied
to other Italian ports too,' says Mr Magnani.
Sceptics say the decision to turn to private companies has come more out of
desperation than desire given the sorry state of the port's finances and the
financial pressures on the Rome government, which has been so generous
towards Genoa in the past. Much of the expected L300bn investment in the
terminals is supposed to come from the private sector. The biggest single
investment - some L75bn - is going on the cruise and ferry terminal, while
L20.5bn is earmarked for the specialised bulk cargo terminal and L47.5bn for
ro-ro.
If the scheme for the terminals is ambitious, that for Voltri is bigger
still. Here, the Port Authority has joined forces with Fiat - a traditional
bogey of the hard left in Italy. Together, they have set up a new company,
Voltri Terminal Europa (VTE), in which Sinport, a subsidiary of Fiat's
Cogefar-Impresit civil engineering arm, has 95 per cent of the shares and
the port the rest. Significantly, overall management will be left to
Sinport, which has been given the concession to run Voltri from the Port
Authority, which controls the land.
When it opens next year, Voltri, covering more than 1m square metres, will
be able to handle three 'jumbo' container ships simultaneously. Volume in
the first year is forecast to reach 100,000 containers, rising to 250,000 in
1995 and 500,000 by the year 2000.
But ambitions for Voltri do not end there. Mr Magnani says the eventual aim
may be to float VTE on the stock market, while other big industrial
shareholders may also be brought in. Such partners could include leading Far
East shipping groups, such as Evergreen, say local industry sources.
Negotiating long-term contracts with big Far Eastern shipping companies is
part of the Port Authority's strategy. 'I know there's a lot of interest,'
Mr Magnani says.
He wants the new facility to become a 'point of reference' in the
Mediterranean, especially given Europe's steadily rising level of imports
from the Far East. The Port Authority plays on Genoa's proximity to Europe's
main markets, which can be reached easily via the adjoining motorway and
rail network. By offloading at Voltri, shippers from the Pacific, sailing
via the Suez canal, would save about a week's journey time compared with
using established container terminals in northern Europe such as Rotterdam.
In spite of having recently returned from an extensive Far Eastern marketing
trip, Mr Magnani will not comment on how close Voltri has come to signing
long-term contracts with big 'round-the-world' shipping groups. Nor will he
reveal whether such companies might become future shareholders in VTE.
However, he draws attention to the fact that a canny group like Fiat is
unlikely to have commited so much money to Voltri if it were unsure about
the outcome.
Mr Magnani admits Voltri may take some business away from the port's two
existing container terminals. However, he notes the facilities are
complementary rather than competitive. Voltri will be able to berth
appreciably bigger ships than can dock in Genoa now. He also points to the
growth of 5-6 per cent a year forecast for Mediterranean traffic. So, while
the old port may lose some business, it should remain busy, he claims. More
important, the lower costs of using Voltri thanks to deregulated labour
could provide a salutary stimulus for altered working practices among the
port's existing dockers.
Surprisingly, Mr Magnani is reticent when it comes to assessing the effect
of Voltri on Marseilles and Barcelona, the two other big container
facilities in the western Mediterranean with which it will compete. 'I don't
say we should be competing with them. Rather, we should be winning back the
business that now goes from Milan to Rotterdam, instead of coming to Genoa,'
he says.
But will Genoa, still bearing the stigma of rotten industrial relations for
many shippers, be able to rise to the new challenges? For many Genoese
businessmen, the port's conversion to the cause of privatisation is hard to
swallow.
Mr Riccardo Garrone, the chairman of the ERG petroleum group and a leader of
the city's business community, responds with scepticism mixed with hope. His
doubts are largely based on the way in which the port has been run in the
past. 'The wrong people were in charge. When motorways were being built all
over Europe, making other, more reliable, ports competitive in spite of
being further away from the main markets, Genoa failed to react.'
The port has undoubtedly lost ground. La Spezia to the south now handles
appreciably more containers, although it is less conveniently placed for the
big cities of northern Italy. Even smaller ports such as Savona have gained
at Genoa's expense.
Mr Garrone focuses on the lack of internal competition and transparency as
the port's biggest problems in the past. Though showered with government
money, the cash went to cover the losses caused by its myriad inefficiencies
rather than being ploughed into investments for the future. Meanwhile, the
regular doses of state funds cushioned dockers and even businesses connected
with the port from feeling the harsh winds of competition, he thinks.
Mr Garrone hopes that part-privatisation and the development of Voltri will
mark a new chapter. But he warns that they will only succeed if there is
genuine competition between port operators. For Mr Garrone, one of the
gravest mistakes of the past was that the port was run by a single, largely
unaccountable entity. Privatisation is definitely 'a step ahead. But there
must true competition' if the schemes are to succeed, he stresses.
</TEXT>
