<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAY 92 / Survey: FT Traveller, Genoa (4) - An international meeting
place / Conferences, The new Congress Centre in the old cotton warehouses
gives the city a high-tech, purpose-built venue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHEN Confindustria, Italy's employers' federation, held its most recent
congress earlier this year, it opted for Genoa. But rather than meeting in
some well-established centre, the 2,000-odd delegates found themselves
occupying the stalls of the Carlo Felice opera house.
The choice of Genoa, and the theatre, probably reflected a desire to promote
the city in Columbus year. And many of the delegates would undoubtedly have
been keen to see the lavishly-restored theatre, which has received heaps of
publicity.
But it also demonstrated Genoa's lack of a suitable venue. Only with the
opening of the new Congress Centre in the converted old cotton warehouses,
which form part of the Expo site, will Genoa be able to boast a high-tech,
purpose-built venue of its own.
Converting the cotton warehouses, built by the British at the beginning of
this century, has been a race against time, with workers in the building
virtually up to a minute before its formal opening with the annual
shareholders' meeting of the Banca Popolare di Genova.
However, visitors are likely to be impressed. With its twin halls on either
side of a central stage, the centre offers flexible seating for up to 1,500,
along with a series of smaller auditoria seating up to 400. There is also a
huge amount of exhibition space on the four floors.
Typical of the iron and brick port architecture of the era, the long, thin
cotton warehouse stretches for almost a quarter of a mile along the Molo
Vecchio wharf jutting out into the harbour. While the exterior has been
largely preserved, much of the interior has been transformed.
The final section housing the conference centre has been gutted. From its
upper floors, delegates will be able to look over the port, while a smaller
building alongside houses all the services, such as sophisticated air
conditioning, needed for a new conference centre. The complex even has its
own telecommunications centre for live teleconferencing.
The congress centre has already lined up five big international conventions
to run concurrently with the Christopher Columbus exhibition, as well as a
range of seminars and lectures. All will focus on maritime issues, including
environmental protection and preservation, as well as legal matters.
The creation of the congress centre means Genoa now has two venues for
conventions, not counting the opera house, which is likely to revert to
full-time cultural use. Over at the fair, the convention centre offers
facilities for up to 800 in its largest auditorium, while a smaller hall can
accommodate around 400 delegates.
Further facilities are available at a number of hotels in the city, notably
the Star, hard by Brignole station in the Corte Lambruschini complex.
However, conference-goers should have an even wider range of choice come
October, when a new hotel is expected to open near the airport, with a range
of meeting halls of its own.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page V
</PAGE>
</DOC>
