<DOCNO>FT922-8065</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEOAZAACFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920515
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAY 92 / Survey: FT Traveller, Genoa (3) - Families dominate the
scene / Business, For many, Genoa still means steel and shipbuilding, though
both have shrunk beyond recognition
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE traditional split in Genoa's business community between a public sector
concentrated in engineering and a private sector specialising in shipping
and trade has been eroded as a result of the crisis in heavy industry and
the part-privatisation of the local steel industry. But the broad
distinction is still valid.
In spite of repeated shrinkage, the giant IRI state holding company remains
Genoa's biggest employer. Its Finmeccanica engineering arm controls Ansaldo,
the city's leading heavy engineering group, whose roots under the Perrone
family go back to the early days of Italy's industrialisation.
Ansaldo has taken some heavy knocks in recent years, notably after the 1987
referendum ban on nuclear power, making the company's nuclear power division
redundant virtually overnight. In spite of that and competition from bigger
international rivals such as Siemens and ABB, Ansaldo has bounced back. Its
Genoese operations are in energy, transportation - especially rail equipment
and signalling - and heavy engineering.
Finmeccanica's other big Genoese offshoot is the Elsag Bailey precision
engineering group. Often presented as one of Italy's high-tech jewels, the
reality is slightly less extravagant. However, the company, which makes a
range of specialised equipment for factory automation, mechanised letter
sorting and various other purposes, has grown rapidly through acquisitions.
After buying the US Bailey group, more than half of sales now come from
abroad, a point stressed heavily in the group's stock market flotation last
year.
For many, Genoa still means steel and shipbuilding, though both have shrunk
beyond recognition. The lavishly renovated headquarters of Ilva, the state
steel group, in an Art-Deco palace in the posh Carignano district, must
count as one of Italy's most impressive corporate headquarters with its
starkly contrasting white interiors, black leather furniture and halogen
lighting.
Ilva's remaining industrial activities, based in the Cornigliano industrial
zone west of the port, are another matter. Most basic steelmaking has long
been moved to southern Italy, while part of the Cornigliano plant has been
privatised. Plans are now in hand to convert much of the remaining
industrial wasteland into a business park for smaller industrial and service
companies as part of Ilva's ambitious but controversial 'Utopia' project.
Most closely identified of all the public-sector companies with the Columbus
Exhibition is IRI's Italimpianti subsidiary, which masterminded the L500bn
building and general contracting project for the Expo site.
Based in a distinctive pencil-shaped tower (the Mattitone) near the western
docks, Italimpianti was merged this year with Italstat, another IRI
subsidiary, into a new group called Iritecna. The aim was to create a large
Italian group combining engineering, contracting and construction skills and
able to compete with foreign rivals such as Germany's Mannesmann and Philipp
Holzmann on big overseas infrastructure projects.
However, Iritecna has so far failed to emerge from the political controversy
and management in-fighting that mar many of its public-sector counterparts.
Many of its problems, like theirs, stem from having too many bosses and
criss-crossing responsibilities.
So while the dream behind Iritecna remains laudable, it will only be
realised if IRI's chairman Mr Franco Nobili, who has a building background,
manages to knock heads together and unblock the difficulties which have so
far paralysed what should be Italy's champion in the international building
and general contracting field.
Genoa is no longer the Italian base for the international oil majors, though
the port remains the country's leading terminal for importing refined
products, which are then distributed nationally or sent on via a direct
pipeline to Switzerland and Germany.
The only big private-sector oil operator left is the Garrone family's ERG
group. Mr Riccardo Garrone, the chairman, is a pugnacious 56-year-old who
assumed control as a youngster after his father died in 1963. Under him, ERG
has grown into Italy's biggest private-sector oil group, with more than
2,000 petrol stations and about 6 per cent of the market.
But even its Genoese activities have slimmed down in recent years. Though
based in the towering World Trade Centre by the docks, most of its
industrial operations are now elsewhere, with a big refinery in Sicily and
other offices in Rome. Genoa remains the nerve centre for top management,
concentrated in the family holding company.
Mr Garrone himself, a keen hunter, is an entrenched critic of the city's
left-wing politicians, whom he accuses of having caused its decline. At last
month's general election, he failed to win a seat in the Senate as a
candidate for the small Republican party. However, his local prestige - and
lavish spending, according to his critics - was enough to lift the party's
share of the vote to 15 per cent from around 4 per cent normally, in spite
of competition from Mr Guido Carli, Italy's treasury minister, and other
candidates.
Genoa's foremost representative in shipping and trade is the privately-owned
Camelli group. Somewhat confusing in its structure after a spate of recent
takeovers of small stock market quoted companies, it now comprises five main
branches.
Camelli concentrates on oil trading, as well as having some refining and
distribution capacity. Gerolimich, a quoted subsidiary, controls various
industrial stakes, both directly and through Unione Manifatture, which is
also quoted and is best known for owning the company making Sweda cash
registers. Other recent acquisitions include Navigazione Alta Italia (NAI)
in shipping and Rodriquez, a shipbuilder famous for its fast catamarans.
Jointly owned by the Camelli family and by Mr Luigi Regis Milano, who
masterminds its affairs, critics say the group now needs to simplify its
structure after the string of takeovers. Meanwhile, trading in the shares of
a number of the quoted subsidiaries is still suspended.
Among Genoa's other top private companies are the Costa group, now most
familiar for its cruise ships which ply the Caribbean and Mediterranean.
Costa Crociere, quoted on the bourse, is all that is left of what was once
one of Italy's foremost private companies, which rivalled and even surpassed
giants such as Fiat and Pirelli. Mr Angelo Costa, a former boss, ranks as
one of the most famous former chairmen of Italy's Confindustria employers'
federation in the early 1950s.
The group's decline is closely associated with that of the port in the
1970s. But the cruise business has led a partial comeback in recent years
and resulted in a string of orders for huge new vessels - albeit at the cost
of a substantial rise in debt.
Completing the list of the city's big shipping and trading families are the
Clericis, whose link with former British partners, the Coes, is enshrined in
the name of their Coeclerici group.
Their Bulkitalia subsidiary owns a fleet of bulk carriers, which used to be
jointly owned with the big Ferruzzi group. However, Mr Giacomo Clerici,
universally known as Jack, bought out Ferruzzi's then boss, Mr Raul Gardini,
to take sole control.
Now in his 80s, Jack Clerici, whose mother was British, ranks as one of
Genoa's grand old men. His international links, particularly with the former
Soviet Union, have won him a reputation akin to that of the legendary Mr
Armand Hammer in the US.
Mr Giovanni Battista (Gaimba) Parodi is probably Genoa's least known
businessman to outsiders. But for many Italians from the city and beyond, he
counts as one of the richest men in the country.
His operations include the quoted Acquedotto de Ferrari Galliera group,
which distributes half the city's drinking water, and a number of activities
in the construction business, as well as a range of financial holdings,
including stakes in big quoted companies such as Pirelli.
The Parodi family's Genoese roots go far back. The former Banca Parodi was
one of the regional institutions swept up in the founding of the Bank of
Italy, and Mr Parodi is today on the board of the central bank.
Another of the grand old men of Genoa, Mr Parodi is every inch the retiring
millionaire. Famous for his modest lifestyle, his quirks reportedly include
being chauffeured in a tiny Fiat mini-car and occupying the former servants
quarters in a family-owned Palazzo in the majestic via Garibaldi.
The Romanengo family has come to prominence outside Genoa only relatively
recently. Last year, its Sci property group was floated on the bourse.
Having already made a mark on the city's skyline with developments such as
the World Trade Centre and other buildings in the big Centro San Benigno
project, Sci, in which Mr Garrone's ERG group now has a 12.75 per cent
stake, is now extending its property development activities abroad.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-8066</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEOAZAABFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920515
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAY 92 / Survey: FT Traveller, Genoa (2) - Famous son repays his home
town / Columbus Exhibition, The attempt to cash in on Genoa's most
celebrated mariner has been done with true Italian panache
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SOMEWHERE underneath the flyover, not far from the container lorries and
next to the apparently interminable road works is the horseshoe-shaped piece
of Genoa's old harbour housing the exhibition on Christopher Columbus, Ships
and the Sea, the reason for the city's present jamboree.
The attempt to cash in on the Columbus business has been done with true
Italian panache, meaning constructive chaos. The paint may still be wet in
patches, the mortar not quite set on every stone, but the exhibition should
open on time. That in itself will be an achievement considering the
landscape of cranes, pick-up trucks and pneumatic drills that dominated the
scene until just a few weeks back.
The project turned into a race against time after early construction work
unearthed the remains of 12th and 14th Century port installations just where
the aquarium was supposed to go. In came the archaeologists and out went the
blueprints as the site had to be redrawn. In the end, the aquarium and other
linked buildings were shifted 50 metres out to sea.
'We knew all along it wouldn't be ready on time,' says Mr Gianfranco Medri,
the managing director for the L750bn Expo project. 'The experts said it
would take five years to have the aquarium fully functioning. We've done it
in less than three, even if all the tanks won't be full yet. But then, we
started a bit late.'
Europe's biggest aquarium, and the second largest in the world, is just one
of the attractions which the Columbus '92 Exhibition hopes will pull in the
crowds to its redeveloped 12-acre site, just minutes from the city centre.
Looking out to sea, visitors will be struck by the restored old cotton
warehouses, now converted into a congress centre and exhibition space, to
their left. On the right, another long jetty shoots out to sea. It will
incorporate the boat-shaped Italian pavilion and the aquarium behind it.
Straight ahead is a huge spider-like structure, the Bigo, rising from the
water, which has become one of the exhibition's symbols. Recalling a giant
ship's crane, it is the brainchild of Genovese architect Renzo Piano, best
known as one of the two partners behind the Pompidou Centre in Paris, who
has had overall responsibility for the design of the exhibition site.
Yet, in spite of all the money and effort behind it, the exhibition is still
having difficulty getting noticed. Pipped at the post by Seville in Spain,
which has used the 500th anniversary of the discovery of the New World to
mount a vast international extravaganza, Genoa has had to look for niches to
justify its belated attempt to honour its most famous son. The resulting
event, which is not just about Columbus, but on the more general theme of
'ships and the sea', has turned out worthy, with a stress on scientific
research and international conferences, but rather dull.
'Seville is a very different thing,' says Mr Merdi. 'Their intentions are
completely different. The site alone is 10 times bigger than ours.'
Wishful thinking? The existence of the much bigger Seville show, which also
started earlier, and the blanket promotion lavished on it, has obliged the
Genovese to think hard about what their Columbus celebration is all about.
'Ours is based on culture. It's designed to appeal to more thoughtful
visitors who will appreciate the exhibits but be just as interested in the
redevelopment of the old port,' he argues.
Genoa, perhaps making virtue out of necessity, stresses its show is neither
Eurodisney nor Seville. For sheer fun, better to head for the outskirts of
Paris. And if the aim is to gawp at a huge international exposition of the
old school, housed in mind-boggling buildings, Spain is the best
destination. But for those who are content with a more limited, and rather
more intellectual treat, Genoa could fit the bill.
Of course, the exhibition is not without its popular attractions, notably
the aquarium. Likewise the crane, which incorporates a 60-metre revolving
glass lift to hoist visitors aloft to admire the harbour and city from the
sort of perspective more familiar to a young midshipman up the mast of his
vessel than a mariner of today. But the feature in Genoa is more the general
redevelopment project and Renzo Piano's aim to 'open the waterfront again
and reunite the city with the sea' than providing the fun of the fair.
The unspoken rivalry with other big European attractions this year and
Genoa's much more modest means and space are among the reasons why the
project has already excited local tempers, especially over how many people
will actually come. The debate has been fuelled by the city's local
newspaper, Il Secolo XIX, whose family owners favoured a rival scheme to
promote the project.
The Expo's organisers are banking on between 3m and 3.5m visitors during the
Expo's three-month run. Others are more sceptical. They question how many
people, especially from outside the city, will be drawn to an event which,
for all its merits, is short of really big attractions for the general
public. And many claim the L25,000 entrance fee is steep for what is on
offer.
'I'm not expecting a big rush from the start,' says Mr Medri. 'We haven't
gone in for the sort of blanket promotion used by Seville and Eurodisney. I
think that approach can be counter-productive as people tend to get fed up
with being bombarded by promotional publicity.'
He hopes interest in Genoa's show will grow steadily through word of mouth.
'Things will start moving after the first two weeks,' he says. But, in a
familiar refrain, he admits that 'we set off late with the promotion'.
The bulk of visitors will come from Genoa itself or the immediate region.
Around two thirds will be Italians, the remainder foreigners, either from
nearby France or others visiting the Riviera for their summer holidays.
The projections recognise that few will be coming to see Genoa itself, in
spite of all the city's efforts to smarten its appearance. Almost all the
Italian visitors will be day-trippers, and the publicity has been
specifically designed for them.
Apart from the Genovese themselves, the organisers expect the exhibition to
appeal to millions of Italians from big cities such as Milan and Turin, both
less than two hours away by train or car. 'We certainly don't expect they
will all sleep in hotels in the city,' notes Mr Medri.
But once the holiday season starts, he hopes for a wider public as
holidaymakers along the Riviera may be tempted to desert the beach and spend
a day seeing the exhibition for themselves.
But the debate about numbers is probably irrelevant when considered against
the exhibition's wider aims. True, it should provide some entertainment for
the Genovese and their neighbours for a few months this spring and summer.
But more important is the event's role in promoting the rediscovery of a
rundown part of the city, yet lying cheek by jowl with some of its finest
houses and shops. Though not on a scale with harbourside redevelopments in
cities such as Baltimore, where hundreds of acres have been revived and
whole new entertainment zones created, the Genoa exhibition has also been
planned with the future of the city in mind.
More than 80 per cent of the site will remain untouched after the exhibition
closes on August 15, compared with the large-scale demolition which usually
follows a big international event of its kind. Once over, visitors will even
be able to see archaeologists at work on the port installations: it was
their discovery which delayed plans for the aquarium.
But the main contribution of the exhibition will be to have made the
Genovese themselves take their city more seriously. Irrespective of the
attendance figures, the exhibition has triggered off an architectural
revival, with restoration schemes going well beyond the old port itself. So,
while Genoa may have served Columbus badly when it failed to finance his
expedition across the Atlantic, its most famous son has repaid his former
home handsomely today.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page III
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-8067</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEOAZAAAFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920515
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAY 92 / Survey: FT Traveller, Genoa (1) - A look back to the future
/ First Impressions, Nowhere else do the normally chauvinistic Italians play
so strongly the foreign card
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'TO UNDERSTAND Genoa, you have to understand the British,' is the cliche
regularly quoted to any remotely Anglo-Saxon visitor to Italy's biggest
port, now belatedly rediscovering its cultural heritage as an instrument to
counter years of economic decline.
Nowhere else do the normally chauvinistic Italians play so strongly the
foreign card. And nowhere else is the link so close with the UK. From
Genoa's heyday in the early Middle Ages as a mercantile city-state and
traditional rival of Venice, the relationship stretches through centuries of
two-way trade and a flow of tourism and culture which has tended to move
more in one direction than the other.
Always important for the British in their Mediterranean commerce, the
arrival of the Suez Canal made Genoa a vital stop for points further east as
well, notably India. Soon, the British aristocrats, who had already
discovered the mild breezes and jasmine gardens of the Riviera on either
side of the city, were joined by less titled, but equally well-heeled,
Britons who made the city and its surroundings a staging post on their way
to India and beyond.
Sojourns in Riviera watering holes became more than just a way of avoiding
the beastly British winter. For those either returning to the UK from the
colonies or just setting out, a spell on the Riviera became an acceptable
way of adjusting to the climatic changes ahead.
Climate and culture also appealed to the region's most famous British
visitors, the Romantic poets. The bay of La Spezia, 75 miles south of Genoa,
is still sometimes sold to the tourists as the 'Bay of Poets'. Byron used to
swim regularly in Portovenere, just north of La Spezia. In 1822, the
Shelleys rented a small house near the village of Lerici opposite. Sailing
along the coast from Leghorn to La Spezia on his way home Shelley drowned.
With the bicentenary of his birth this year, the number of British literary
tourists is bound to surge.
Genoa still makes much of its Anglo-Saxon links, a factor often cited today
to explain its charms and failings. For fellow Italians, the Genovese are a
dull lot; cool and reserved, they speak a barely comprehensible dialect and
seldom display the extrovert verve usually associated with their fellow
nationals. Like the Piedmontese to the north, they are also known throughout
Italy for a caution with money which is associated more with the Scottish
than the English.
The Anglo-Saxon air still hangs over parts of the city, though more in terms
of manners and society than art or architecture. Though exaggerated by their
fellow Italians, the tradition of reserve remains. Genoa's rich do not
flaunt their wealth like those in Milan and especially Rome. Money is
suggested rather than seen behind the high hedges and wrought-iron gates of
their big villas perched on the hills near the Staglieno cemetery towering
over the city.
Visitors to Genoa are often carted off to Finollo, an old-fashioned tie and
shirt maker on elegant via Roma, to savour for themselves the city's
Anglo-Saxon air. The dark and narrow store, full of ties in regimental
stripes, certainly recalls some of its counterparts in London's Jermyn
Street. But it is a measure of popular misunderstanding about the UK that
the shop, whose proprietors seem to have confused the distant politeness of
the British with a patronising smugness, verging on the rude, should so
often be used as a showcase.
Such self-satisfaction is at the heart of many of Genoa's problems, which
have dogged it for decades and which partly explain why its corner of the
famous economic triangle with Milan and Turin has shown signs of lapsing.
'Genoa's error is a bit like the problems of the British,' says Mr Carlo Da
Molo, chairman of Italgas, one of Italy's leading companies, and a born
Genovese.
Over the past three decades, the city failed to adapt to changing economic
circumstances and continued to rely heavily on the port as its main source
of livelihood. 'They didn't appreciate that things were changing', says Mr
Riccardo Garrone, a leading Genovese businessman whose ERG group is the
biggest private-sector petroleum company in Italy.
The complaints are levelled as much at the state as the private sector.
After the Second World War, public money poured into the bomb-scarred city
to rebuild heavy industry and set up new activities, notably in steel.
Meanwhile, more cash was ploughed into the port, as much in later years to
cover inefficiencies and restrictive labour practices as to adapt to new
trends, such as containerisation.
Change came only when the political balance tilted away from the hard left,
which dominated both the port and local politics, or when the inefficiencies
of both became too obvious to ignore.
The bell began to toll for the steel industry in the late 1960s, when
production started to shift to southern Italy. Though largely a political
decision, the move was also in recognition of the fact that Genoa's narrow
coastal strip, bounded by mountains and the sea, hardly lent itself to the
development of large-scale, integrated steelworks. Meanwhile, shipbuilding
suffered at the hands of cheaper foreign competition, and production of the
biggest vessels was eventually concentrated elsewhere.
Yet, the accusation of short-sightedness is levelled as strongly at Genoa's
private sector. Geared to shipping and trade, the city boasts next to no
private-sector industry, apart from the small Piaggio aircraft group and the
remains of the now partly-privatised steel business.
Showing native caution, Genoa's businessmen tended to stick to what they
knew best, maintaining their traditions as merchants rather than
entrepreneurs. Others suffered indirectly from the slow decline of the port.
'There were no industrialists in the private sector,' says Mr Garrone. 'And
the big private companies that did exist were too divided among themselves
to organise as a lobby to press for change'. Arguably, the development of
much better communications from the late 1950s, with excellent motorway
links between Genoa and the big cities of the north, may have encouraged the
tendency towards individualism. Local businessmen, frustrated by left-wing
politics locally, may have preferred to invest in the growing areas of
Lombardy and Piedmont to the north rather than Genoa itself. Others may have
chosen the less legal, but well-trodden, route to Switzerland for their
flight capital.
'Our refinery had to be closed because its chimneys released private-sector
smoke,' recalls a still bitter Mr Garrone. 'But the fumes from the Italsider
steelworks were good, because they were public-sector fumes,' he says
angrily. 'Mind you, as soon as it went private, it also came under attack.'
Though most critical of the hard left councils which governed Genoa for
years, he sees the city's recent past as having been tainted with a general
hostility to the private sector that went beyond the Communists to influence
other political groups, too.
The changes in Genoa today may be too sudden and dramatic to last. But the
optimists hope financial stringency in the public-sector will prove salutary
in stimulating a concentration only on activities which are viable. At the
port, partial privatisation of some operations and the construction of a
huge new container terminal at Voltri to the west have offered the chance of
regaining a role as the foremost trading post in the Mediterranean.
Meanwhile, local politics have taken a significant move towards the centre
with the arrival of a soft-left council two years ago.
Looking ahead, many Genovese point to the Christopher Columbus exhibition as
providing the spur to regenerate after decades of delay. Further off, but
even more important in its potential economic effect, is the planned
high-speed rail link with Milan.
That could cut the journey time from two hours to around 40 minutes. But
rather than seeing themselves as potential losers to their bigger neighbour
to the north, the Genovese are confident their city will be the clear
beneficiary from such an improvement in communications.
The link would make the coast far more accessible to northern Italians, for
whom Genoa would be the gateway. It may not trigger the development of new
heavy industry, but the high-speed line could be just the incentive for
creating the new service sector activities the city is looking for.
</TEXT>
