FT  14 MAY 92 / International Company News: Time Inc moves into in-store
advertising
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TIME Incorporated, the magazine and book publishing subsidiary of the Time
Warner group, is to acquire Media One, an in-store advertising company.
Terms of the deal were not disclosed, but it is believed to have cost Time
around Dollars 20m.
Media One, which is based in New York, is the second biggest in-store
advertising company in the US. It has a network of display units in more
than 6,000 grocery stores including big chains such as Safeway, Kroger and
Winn-Dixie.
The company's most recognisable product is a two-sided display at
supermarket check-out counters.
Time, which is making its first foray into the advertising business with
this acquisition, said it planned to offer Media One's display products to
prospective advertisers in the company's magazine division.
In a separate development, Time Warner said a consortium of banks led by
Bankers Trust and Chemical bank had given a commitment that a previously
disclosed Dollars 6.2bn new loan facility would be available by the end of
June.
It emerged last month that Time Warner was seeking to reschedule more than
Dollars 7bn of debt, substantial amounts of which would have begun coming
due next year. The centrepiece of the plan was to stretch out repayments of
principal with the new and longer term Dollars 6.2bn loan.
Another part of the plan was the raising of Dollars 850m by way of a recent
private placement and a commitment from Merrill Lynch to provide Dollars
250m of bridging loans, to be replaced later this year by a 10-year bond
issue.
