<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 92 / International Company News: O&amp;Y seeks extra funds for
Canadian operations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON, ALAN FRIEDMAN and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
OLYMPIA &amp; York wants lenders to provide extra funds for its Canadian
operations before paying CDollars 17m (USDollars 14.2m) in overdue interest
on a series of publicly-traded bonds secured by Toronto's tallest office
building.
It also emerged yesterday that bankers in a loan syndicate led by JP Morgan
are so infuriated by a recent O&amp;Y decision to divert cash on a collateral
property from bank creditors to bondholders that they have decided to
foreclose on a Dollars 160m O&amp;Y loan made last year.
The foreclosure - to occur next week - would be the first seizure of O&amp;Y
assets since the restructuring of the Canadian property group's debt began.
It places Morgan in an awkward spot since the bank is serving as both a
financial adviser to O&amp;Y and a creditor with an estimated Dollars 50m of
total loan exposure.
Sir Dennis Weathertone, Morgan's chairman, yesterday defended the
foreclosure move and said it would not lead to a collapse of the overall O&amp;Y
debt restructuring. 'We're confident we've done the right thing,' he told
Morgan's annual meeting.
Meanwhile, Canadian banks have yet to respond to O&amp;Y's request to draw down
the remaining USDollars 130m of a USDollars 240m facility provided by four
Canadian banks.
The cash-strapped developer has indicated that without these funds it is
unable to pay interest due on CDollars 325m in bonds secured by the
72-storey First Canadian Place.
It has also failed to retire about CDollars 150m in commercial paper secured
by the Exchange Tower, a 36-storey building adjacent to First Canadian
Place.
Interest on the bonds came due last week, but under the bond covenants, O&amp;Y
has various grace periods which expire tomorrow.
O&amp;Y says it has made a compromise proposal to the bondholders' trustee,
Royal Trust.
O&amp;Y yesterday ended the second day of its fight to stave off a potentially
damaging demand for Dollars 240m in the High Court in London, but no ruling
was made, Reuter reports.
The appeal, which is being heard in private, is over the timing of the
payment owed by the group to Morgan Stanley, the US investment bank.
The hearing will continue today, when a ruling could be made. If O&amp;Y loses
its appeal, the money becomes due immediately.
</TEXT>
