FT  14 MAY 92 / Parliament and Politics: Smith and Gould back reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR must reject the notion that minor policy changes will prove adequate
to win the next election and instead develop a platform with an appeal that
embraces the interests and aspirations of middle-class voters.
That is the view held by both contenders for the party leadership in
articles published in New Statesman and Society magazine today.
Shadow chancellor Mr John Smith, the odds-on favourite, and Mr Bryan Gould,
his challenger, definitively reject the so-called 'one last heave' notion,
which argues that the party should simply repackage its current policies and
improve on its communications with the electorate.
But their approaches to broadening the party's appeal vary subtly, with Mr
Gould delivering a thinly-veiled attack on his rival for his handling of
economic policy.
Mr Smith argues that Labour should play heavily on the argument of
enlightened self-interest, a broad concept of freedom and economic logic.
The shadow chancellor suggests that the 'comfortable and contented' are
anxious about inner-city degeneration, unemployment and the decline in the
quality of life.
Mr Gould begins by criticising Labour's election campaign for failing to
offer motives to middle-class voters to support the party.
In a passage that will infuriate Mr Smith's supporters, he says the party
endorsed Tory macroeconomic policies by accepting a simple goal of monetary
stability, offering no route to full employment or recovery. He also asks
why constructive proposals such as contributors' control over pensions
funds, share ownership schemes and better employee rights were not proposed.
In future, electors should not be treated as socio-economic groups but as
individuals given the power that leaves them 'properly equipped to operate
in a market place that would otherwise treat them unfairly'.
</TEXT>
