<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 92 / Parliament and Politics: Chancellor upbeat on growth aims
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S return to economic growth would become 'firmly established' in
1992, Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, told the Commons last night.
Confidently predicting a further reduction in inflation he said: 'We have a
once-in-a-generation chance to push towards price stability'.
The chancellor hoped for an increase in demand as the tax cuts made in the
March Budget reached pay packets next week, and home-buyers used the extra
money at their disposal through reductions in mortgage interest payments.
He expected some of the increase in disposable incomes would 'feed through
into higher consumer spending'.
Mr Lamont's optimism contrasted with the judgment of Mr John Smith, shadow
chancellor and front runner in Labour's leadership contest, who, on the
final day of the debate on the Queen's Speech, led an attack on the
government's continuing failure to halt the rise in unemployment.
The chancellor also came under fire from Mr Neil Kinnock, the Labour leader,
over his refusal to state the year in which the objective of returning to a
balanced budget 'in the medium term' would be achieved.
Mr Lamont stressed that he was not 'altering in any way' the forecast of a
Pounds 28bn public sector borrowing requirement in the current financial
year.
The published figures for the PSBR in subsequent years - including the
Pounds 32bn for 1993-94 - were 'assumptions' and not forecasts.
The chancellor claimed that the projection for the last year covered by the
table in the Budget Red Book - which Mr Kinnock emphasised was Pounds 6bn -
was 'very close to balance indeed'.
Mr Lamont said the uncertainty caused by the possibility of a Labour victory
in the general election had held back company investment and orders, and
subdued consumer demand.
Now the message from forward-looking surveys of business and consumer
confidence was clear, and the stock market and foreign exchange markets had
signalled their renewed confidence in the government's policies.
He emphasised,too, that with last week's  1/2 percentage point cut in bank
rate the differential between British and German interest rates had been
reduced from about 7 per cent to just a quarter of one per cent, lower than
at any time in the past decade.
Thanks to the government's refusal to bow to short-term pressures, Britain's
inflation performance had improved out of all recognition, he said.
Underlying producer-output price inflation was lower than at any time since
the early 1970s, and he expected it to fall to below 2 per cent in 1993.
The chancellor emphasised the need to control public expenditure, but Mr
Smith deplored the lack of any reference in the Queen's Speech to
unemployment and the recession, and accused Tory MPs of being interested
only in 'the level of their shares on the Stock Exchange'.
He said the government had failed to foster the manufacturing sector - the
wealth-producing sector of the economy.
To taunts from Tory backbenchers over the outcome of the election, Mr Smith
said Labour's defeat did not alter the fact that investment was falling,
unemployment rising and that the government had failed to support industry.
He warned that Britain had no future as a low cost, low-skilled
'bargain-basement economy'.
</TEXT>
