<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PROPOSALS unveiled yest-erday by the Auditing Practices Board may create
extra costs and impose additional responsibilities on directors and
auditors, experts warned yesterday.
The plans were welcomed by Mr Roger Davis, head of audit at Coopers &amp;
Lybrand Deloitte, the accountancy firm. However, he warned that auditors
would be put on the spot by the proposed requirement to express an opinion
on whether a company was a going concern for the following 12 months.
Mr Hugh Collum, chairman of the 100 Group of leading finance directors, said
the going concern statement was an important contribution but 'it's going to
need careful handling, particularly for companies in difficulties.'
The Confederation of British Industry commented: 'It puts a heavy burden on
directors and auditors.'
The proposal for an expanded report spelling out that directors and not
auditors are responsible for the accounts giving a true and fair view of the
business was welcomed by the Institute of Directors.
A report commissioned by the Institute of Chartered Accountants in England
and Wales said that an expanded report would be useful in reducing the
'expectations gap' in public understanding of the role of auditors.
