<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 92 / Councils criticised over planning
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MOST councils are failing to meet government targets for faster planning
decisions in spite of a fall in development activity, the Audit Commission
says in a report published today.
The government spending watchdog says only a handful of English councils are
satisfying the target of deciding 80 per cent of planning applications
within eight weeks. The target was set in 1982 by Mr Michael Heseltine, then
environment secretary.
The commission says the proportion of applications decided within eight
weeks declined from 70 per cent in 1982-83 to 46 per cent in 1989-90. It
adds that there has been only a small improvement since 1989-90 in spite of
a fall in applications and a rise in staff.
The commission says councils should take advantage of lower workloads to
streamline and improve their planning procedures.
The report was welcomed yesterday by the Conservative-led Association of
District Councils; the Association of London Authorities, which represents
most Labour London boroughs; and the Council for the Protection of Rural
England (CPRE), the environmental group.
Mr Tony Burton, senior planner at the CPRE, warned, however, that 'proper
protection for the countryside cannot be secured by rushed planning
decisions to meet artificial deadlines imposed by the government'.
During 1990-91, English local authorities made decisions on 518,000 planning
applications compared with more than 600,000 applications in each of the two
preceding years. Applications last year, however, were still 40 per cent
higher than 10 years before.
Mr Bob Chilton, local government director at the commission, said: 'Having
survived the pressures of the development boom of the late 1980s, local
authorities should use the current easing in the volume of applications to
assess the quality of the local service they provide and to prepare for the
next surge in applications.'
The commission said that time wasted in administration could be put to
better use in improving assessment procedures and providing greater public
consultation. It urged planning departments to avoid wasting time by setting
clear objectives and providing opportunities for discussion and advice
before developers submitted formal applications.
Audit Commission: Building in Quality, A Study of Development Control. HMSO
Pounds 8.50.
</TEXT>
