<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 92 / Big rise reported in formation of company audit committees
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANY British companies have created audit committees voluntarily in the past
few years, but few disclose much about them in their accounts, according to
a report commissioned by the Institute of Chartered Accountants in England
and Wales.
A sample of 300 organisations was polled and replies were received from 202
industrial concerns, including listed companies, and 44 financial
institutions.
Two thirds of the industrial concerns and 88 per cent of the institutions
had audit committees, compared with 17 per cent of large UK companies in a
1985 study
Mr Paul Collier, a lecturer in accounting at Exeter University who carried
out the research for the institute early last year, said greater levels of
control and the requirement for compliance committees explained the higher
incidence among financial institutions.
The typical audit committee has one executive director and three or four
non-executive directors, appointed for an indefinite period. It meets three
times a year and reviews company accounting principles and practice. Half of
the committees in the survey review auditors' fees.
But the annual reports of 45 per cent of the industrial concerns and 21 per
cent of the institutions did not disclose even the presence of an audit
committee. Among industrial concerns, many public-sector organisations and
listed companies had audit committees, while other businesses and the
subsidiaries of foreign-owned companies had very few.
More than half of the committees had been created within the previous five
years. The most frequently cited reasons for their creation were good
corporate practice and strengthening the effectiveness of non-executive
directors.
Many companies without audit committees dismissed them as an additional
layer of bureaucracy, and said that their costs would outweigh their
benefits.
Audit Committees in Large UK Companies. Technical Dept, ICAEW, PO Box 433,
London EC2P 2BJ. Pounds 15.
</TEXT>
