<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 92 / Holiday operators expect a tough year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD and BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN EXPECTED post-election boom in package holidays has failed to
materialise, leaving tour operators facing a second difficult year.
A number of tour operators have cut the price of holidays in May and June by
as much as 60 per cent to fill empty seats - in some cases up to a quarter
of their capacity. With Thomson, the largest operator, last-minute
bargain-seekers can buy for Pounds 199 a fly-drive holiday to Florida which
would normally cost more than Pounds 400.
Analysts also point to a new trend for holidaymakers to wait longer before
making bookings, depriving tour operators of the benefit of early deposits.
The move to last-minute bookings means that tour operators now have less
cash on deposit earning interest over several months.
The Civil Aviation Authority yesterday published figures showing that tour
operators had overcapacity of 1.6m holidays in the 12 months to September 30
last year and a turnover of Pounds 440m less than the tour industry had
predicted.
The 40 largest operators had obtained CAA licences for 11.9m passengers, but
actually carried only 10.3m. This year, tour operators have told the
authority they expect to carry 13.5m passengers, an increase of more than 30
per cent on last year's actual figures.
Authority licences for this year project turnover of Pounds 4.44bn, a
substantial increase on both the forecast for 1990-91 (Pounds 3.65bn) and
the turnover achieved (Pounds 3.21bn).
Thomas Cook, the travel agent, said yesterday that those in the industry who
expected 'a post-election expansion of package holiday demand' had been
disappointed.
Holidays for May and June have 'not been selling as well as would have been
liked' but Thomas Cook said the case would be different in the latter part
of June through to September. Summer bookings - where discounting has not
yet been necessary - are already 'full to the brim'.
Thomas Cook believes that the projections by some operators of an increase
of 20 per cent to 40 per cent in demand this year is over-optimistic. 'Those
which are looking for a 7 per cent to 10 per cent increase are being more
realistic', it said.
Mr Harry Coe, group finance director of Airtours, the third largest
operator, said the level of discounting was not unusual. 'Every year there
is excess capacity in May and June, and every year there is price-cutting in
the late bookings market in order to move it,' he said.
Lex, Page 20
</TEXT>
