<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 92 / Health trust managers strive for a new relationship: Lisa
Wood and Catherine Milton on the effects of government reforms on industrial
relations in the NHS
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD and CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONE OF THE most immediate effects of government reforms to the National
Health Service is likely to be on employee relations.
Many personnel managers in the new self-governing trusts, which are allowed
to set their own pay and conditions, are examining ways of leaving national
agreements.
But a Financial Times survey of more than half of the first 57 NHS trusts
which came into existence just over a year ago shows that most are initially
moving with caution.
Mr Bob Rotchell, director of operations at West Dorset Community NHS Trust,
said that nationally agreed terms and conditions in the health service had
been a 'personnel manager's nightmare'. Like most trust managers, however,
he said the devolution to trusts of managerial responsibility for industrial
relations was not easy. 'Any group who thought when they established a trust
that setting local pay and conditions would be easy must have been very
naive,' he said.
Nevertheless, greater flexibility should eventually mean a smaller,
better-trained NHS workforce. Within weeks of becoming self-governing a year
ago, Guy's and Lewisham Trust in London announced plans to shed several
hundred jobs to cut Pounds 5m from labour costs. The trust is now balancing
its books and has given lower-paid staff an extra Pounds 5 per week above
national rates, but Mr Peter Griffiths, chief executive, expects the trust
to operate with up to 20 per cent fewer staff in Guy's hospital in five
years. Such reductions are likely to become widespread in the health
service. The jobs of its many unskilled ancillary workers and of some
laboratory and other technical staff will be at risk.
The FT survey also highlights managers' ambitions for an overhaul of the
traditional negotiating machinery. Most trusts want a single pay spine, or
scale, for all their employees. That would replace the dozen or so present
scales, including those negotiated by the Whitley Councils, which have
traditionally set pay and conditions in the NHS. It would also replace the
newer pay review bodies for nurses, doctors and professions allied to
medicine.
An overhaul would facilitate local pay bargaining. The government says it
will not abolish national machinery, but it could become redundant or, at
best, a 'benchmark' for local deals. Bradford Hospital Trust said: 'Nobody
will be worse off. Whitley is regarded as a minimum.'
All trusts in the survey agreed that pay would not be squeezed as a result
of the changes. Most said they were affected by skill shortages and the need
to attract staff, but Southend Health Care Trust warned: 'In some cases we
will pay more than Whitley and, if we don't need to, we won't'
Harmonising conditions for employees could, in the short-term, increase pay
bills. But the process is likely to be linked to greater flexibility.
Several trusts are taking on new healthcare assistants to assist trained
nurses in wards from which student nurses are being removed. United Bristol
Healthcare Trust said: 'As the number of people available as nationally
trained nurses falls, so we will be forced to take on more people who are
trained locally.'
Other findings of the survey include:
Only a few trusts have negotiated formal recognition agreements with unions.
A few were reluctant to discuss the issue, including Central Middlesex
Hospital and Nuffield Orthopaedic Trust.
One, West Dorset Community Health Trust, has successfully agreed and
implemented a pay package, including a local performance pay deal, with
unions this year. Homewood Trust in Chertsey, Surrey, has agreed with unions
a package that includes what is in effect a no-strike deal. But no local pay
offer has yet been agreed. Northumbria Ambulance Trust has awarded employees
a local pay deal this year, but it was negotiated with the Association of
Professional Ambulance Personnel (Apap), a union not affiliated to the
Trades Union Congress. Apap has been given sole negotiating rights at the
trust.
No other first-wave trusts plan to give sole rights to a union, although
most want single-table bargaining, in which several unions appoint
representatives to conduct joint negotiations. Cohse, the health-service
union, says that only 15 trusts have signed formal agreements with unions to
negotiate over pay and conditions.
Acas, the conciliation service, sees great strides in employment
relationship among trusts. It adds, however, that 'there often remains a
lack of expertise in this area among local managers and trade union
representatives alike'.
Most trusts in the survey offered slightly different conditions of
employment in contracts offered to new staff. Mr Brian Carpenter, personnel
director of South Devon Healthcare Trust, said it had introduced changes to
time off and had brought in performance-related pay for senior managers.
Changes made by other trusts include limiting appeal rights and adjustments
to maternity leave.
Many trusts are using outside consultants to investigate job evaluation.
Nine trusts in the south-west of England are working together on
investigating job evaluation, a system trusts say could add to wage bills.
Mr Rotchell of West Dorset said he had been told by consultants that the
exercise could add 5 per cent.
Most trusts want a single pay spine covering all staff although a few said
such ambitions would be hard to realise because of the complexity of
arranging so many groups of staff on one scale. Southend said it would like
five or six spines and proposed big changes such as abolishing the increment
related to length of service. It did not plan to introduce
performance-related pay.
Harmonisation of terms and conditions is favoured by trusts, but all agreed
that such a move would incur costs.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 7
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-8138</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CENCNAFLFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920514
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 92 / Eggar seeks power price cut
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIET SYCHRAVA and ANDREW SLADE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE electricity industry must cut domestic bills to reflect cheaper coal
prices, Mr Tim Eggar, energy minister, said yesterday.
Mr Eggar, speaking during a visit to Rufford and Ollerton collieries in
Nottinghamshire, said it was vital that consumers were given the benefit of
any deal between the electricity producers and British Coal.
He was confident British Coal would be able to produce coal at prices that
would benefit electricity consumers. 'The challenge that faces this and
other pits is to reduce their costs to produce coal competitively,' he
added. 'It is a challenge I am convinced British Coal can meet.' Mr Eggar
said it was important for British Coal to be privatised without delay. This
meant that it must agree contracts to sell coal to the electricity industry
as soon as possible. These contracts would determine how many British Coal
pits would survive, Mr Eggar added.
He would not confirm rumours that the government was about to negotiate an
agreement between British Coal and the electricity industry. He saw a role
for the government as a 'facilitator'.
The government, British Gas, the regulatory body Ofgas and 11 of the
regional electricity companies in England and Wales are to set up an
independent Energy Savings Trust to promote the efficient use of energy,
Andrew Slade writes.
The initiative promised in the Conservatives' general election manifesto was
announced yesterday by Mr Michael Howard, environment secretary. His
department said the government expected funding to come from the electricity
industry and consumers. a
</TEXT>
