<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 92 / CBI survey points to recovery areas: Yorkshire and
Humberside region, east Midlands and Wales are expected to lead growth in
services and manufacturing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WALES, the east Midlands, and the Yorkshire and Humberside region are likely
to lead the economic recovery, according to the Business Strategies
consultancy.
Its conclusion is based on a regional breakdown released yesterday of
prospects for manufacturers, conducted by the consultancy with the
Confederation of British Industry.
Ms Bridget Rosewell, joint managing director of Business Strategies, said
the three regions all combined relative strength in manufacturing with
reasonably good prospects for services - which account for about three
quarters of gross domestic product.
The study is based on the CBI's quarterly industrial trends survey, which
questioned 1,328 manufacturing companies between March 27 and April 13.
According to the study, manufacturers across the UK are generally more
optimistic than four months ago. Expectations about a recovery were
particularly marked in East Anglia, the south-east and the west Midlands.
All three areas were hit hard in the early stages of the recession in 1990.
However, the north of England and Scotland - two regions relatively little
affected in the early part of the recession - appear to be suffering more
now in terms of depressed orders and output.
Out of the 11 UK regions, five have seen a decrease in the past year in the
proportion of companies working below capacity. These are the south-east,
East Anglia, Yorkshire and Humberside, east Midlands and Wales.
Most regions have continued over the past four months to see a fall in
output and orders, but at a lower rate than last year.
Another relatively gloomy conclusion is that all regions except the north
expect a decline in investment in plant and machinery over the next 12
months.
The expected rate of reduction in capital spending appears to be slowing in
the east and west Midlands and Wales.
</TEXT>
