<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 92 / Debts soar among Russian enterprises
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD and LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RUSSIA'S enterprises had piled up Rbs1.43 trillion (million million) in
debts to each other and to the banks by May 1, the central bank said
yesterday. This sum is greater than the country's gross national product for
the first quarter.
Mr Vyacheslav Solovov, the bank's vice-chairman, said inter-enterprise debts
were increasing at the rate of Rbs27.5bn a day.
Talks are under way between the government, central bank and parliament on
ways to solve this rapidly gathering crisis - including debt forgiveness and
a bigger budget deficit.
Yesterday, the government more than doubled teachers' and doctors' pay after
they had threatened to strike for a 10-fold increase. The two groups are
among the poorest in Russia, earning about Rbs700 a month (the minimum wage
has just been increased to Rbs900).
The government also announced plans to levy import taxes of 5-10 per cent to
reduce the import bill. These will come into effect in August, and they
follow a 13 per cent increase in first-quarter imports, compared with a year
ago. That pushed the balance of payments deficit for the period to Dollars
2bn. Mr Pyotr Aven, foreign economic relations minister, told Interfax news
agency that the government was also considering an extra 28 per cent VAT on
imports.
Meanwhile, Mr Georgy Matiukhin, central bank chairman, said the system of
trade between the main republics of the former Soviet Union was increasingly
breaking down.
</TEXT>
