<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 92 / Business leaders say Tecs on brink of collapse
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART and ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NATIONAL training structure is on a 'knife-edge' and may collapse unless
the government gives greater freedom from Whitehall interference to the
1,000 business leaders responsible for running it.
A confidential memorandum to Mrs Gillian Shephard, the employment secretary,
from leaders of the 82 Training and Enterprise Councils warns that without
'major reform' the 1,000 senior executives running the Tecs 'will simply
walk away'.
'There will be no mass protest,' says the memo from G10, the body which
represents Tecs to government. 'But their effectiveness will drain away into
the sand of inertia'.
The Tec leaders are scathing about the extent of Whitehall bureaucracy and
the absence of a clear cross-government approach to training. They say that
Tec successes are now jeopardised by 'a welter of administrative procedures'
and cite interference in their accounting and business methods from
Department of Employment officials.
They are particularly anxious to win more discretion in the way they manage
the two main training programmes: Youth Training, which provides up to two
years' training for 300,000 under 18s, and Employment Training, which
provides up to one year's training for 149,000 long-term unemployed adults.
Very few of these trainees currently go on to jobs.
They doubt whether it is cost effective to retain the existing guarantees of
a place on either ET or YT and claim it cannot be done without additional
funding.
The document continues: 'There is a conflict between the strategic focus of
national targets . . . and the pressure of the guarantee for unemployed
young people on the other. There must be proper public funding to meet this
guarantee without seriously eroding the longer-term build up of national
skill levels.'
The issues of targets and flexibility will come to a head next week in talks
between Tec leaders and Mrs Shephard. She may be ready to give some ground
if it does not involve abandoning the training guarantees. Loosening these
would be controversial and might raise headline unemployment. Today, the
unemployment figure for April is expected to rise by about 25,000.
Mr Tony Blair, Labour's employment spokesman, said more flexibility for Tecs
might be desirable but 'it would be disgraceful if there were any reduction
in help for the growing numbers of unemployed'.
The Tec leaders want tax breaks for companies meeting the demanding
Investors in People training standard. Only 50 companies have done so. They
also want much greater Tec involvement in the careers service, currently run
by local authorities.
</TEXT>
